DB["Use of English"][5] = [

  // -- COMPREHENSION PASSAGE 1 --
  {
    section: "Comprehension",
    passage: `The Nigerian film industry, popularly known as Nollywood, has emerged as the second largest film industry in the world by volume of output, producing over 2,500 films annually. From its humble origins in the early 1990s, when low-budget films were distributed directly on VHS tapes, Nollywood has evolved into a multi-billion dollar industry with global reach. Its stories, rooted in Nigerian culture, family dynamics, and spiritual tension, have found audiences across Africa, the Caribbean, and the Nigerian diaspora in Europe and North America.\n\nYet the industry faces persistent structural challenges. The vast majority of productions are still made on shoestring budgets that preclude high production values, and piracy continues to haemorrhage revenue. Distribution remains fragmented, with cinemas concentrated in affluent urban areas and largely inaccessible to the majority of Nigerians. The emergence of streaming platforms such as Netflix, which has invested significantly in Nigerian content, has opened new revenue streams, though critics argue this risks homogenising storytelling to suit international tastes rather than domestic ones.\n\nDefenders of Nollywood's current trajectory point to its unmatched cultural authenticity. Unlike Hollywood productions that often flatten African narratives into stereotypes, Nollywood films reflect the complexity and diversity of Nigerian life with an intimacy that resonates deeply with local audiences. The challenge for the next decade is to improve technical quality and distribution infrastructure without sacrificing the cultural rootedness that is the industry's greatest competitive advantage.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_1", question:"According to the passage, what distinguishes Nollywood globally by volume?", options:{A:"It is the most profitable film industry in the world",B:"It is the second largest film industry by number of films produced annually",C:"It is the oldest film industry in Africa",D:"It has the highest cinema attendance in the world"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The passage states Nollywood is 'the second largest film industry in the world by volume of output, producing over 2,500 films annually.' The question tests precise retrieval. Profitability and attendance are not mentioned." },
      { id:"en5_2", question:"The word 'haemorrhage' as used in the passage most nearly means:", options:{A:"Increase substantially",B:"Regulate carefully",C:"Cause a severe and damaging loss of",D:"Generate through illegal means"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Haemorrhage literally means severe bleeding. Used figuratively here, 'piracy continues to haemorrhage revenue' means piracy causes a severe and ongoing loss of income. The metaphor likens money lost to blood bleeding from a wound." },
      { id:"en5_3", question:"Which concern do critics raise about streaming platforms investing in Nollywood?", options:{A:"That streaming reduces cinema attendance permanently",B:"That international investment may lead to storytelling being shaped to suit global rather than local tastes",C:"That Nigerian producers are losing copyright ownership",D:"That streaming platforms pay below-market rates"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Critics argue the streaming investment 'risks homogenising storytelling to suit international tastes rather than domestic ones.' Homogenising means making uniform, sacrificing local distinctiveness for broader appeal." },
      { id:"en5_4", question:"The word 'preclude' as used in the passage most nearly means:", options:{A:"Guarantee",B:"Encourage",C:"Prevent or make impossible",D:"Delay significantly"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Preclude means to prevent something from happening or make it impossible. Shoestring budgets 'preclude high production values' means the tiny budgets make high quality production impossible." },
      { id:"en5_5", question:"What does the writer identify as Nollywood's greatest competitive advantage?", options:{A:"Its high production budgets",B:"Its large cinema network",C:"Its cultural authenticity and rootedness",D:"Its partnership with international streaming platforms"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The final paragraph explicitly states: 'the cultural rootedness that is the industry's greatest competitive advantage.' The writer contrasts this with Hollywood's flattened African stereotypes. Options A and B are described as weaknesses, not strengths." }
    ]
  },

  // -- COMPREHENSION PASSAGE 2 --
  {
    section: "Comprehension",
    passage: `Road traffic accidents remain one of Nigeria's most devastating and preventable public health crises. The country loses an estimated 40,000 lives annually on its roads, a toll that surpasses many infectious diseases yet receives a fraction of the policy attention. Factors contributing to this carnage are well documented: deplorable road conditions, ageing vehicle fleets, widespread non-compliance with traffic regulations, driver fatigue, and the pervasive culture of impunity among commercial drivers who routinely exceed speed limits and overload their vehicles without consequence.\n\nBeyond the human tragedy, road accidents impose enormous economic costs. Victims are often economically active members of their families and communities, and their deaths or disablement trigger cascading poverty. Hospitals are overwhelmed with trauma cases that consume disproportionate shares of scarce medical resources. The Federal Road Safety Corps (FRSC), tasked with enforcing traffic laws, is under-resourced and undermined by corruption that allows violators to pay bribes rather than face prosecution.\n\nNigeria's road safety crisis demands an integrated response. Physical infrastructure must be upgraded and maintained. Vehicles must be subjected to rigorous roadworthiness certification. Driver licensing must be reformed to ensure genuine competence rather than purchased certificates. Above all, a culture of accountability must replace the current culture of impunity. Experts argue that political will, not resources, is the binding constraint. The technology and knowledge exist; what is lacking is the will to enforce.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_6", question:"How many lives does Nigeria lose annually on its roads, according to the passage?", options:{A:"About 4,000",B:"About 14,000",C:"About 40,000",D:"About 400,000"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The passage states 'The country loses an estimated 40,000 lives annually on its roads.' This is a direct retrieval question. Numbers are frequently tested in JAMB comprehension, so always read carefully." },
      { id:"en5_7", question:"The word 'carnage' as used in the passage most nearly means:", options:{A:"Infrastructure damage",B:"Mass killing or slaughter",C:"Economic loss",D:"Political corruption"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Carnage means the killing of a large number of people. The passage uses it to refer to the mass loss of life on Nigerian roads. The context (40,000 deaths, deplorable conditions) confirms this meaning." },
      { id:"en5_8", question:"According to the passage, how does corruption affect road safety enforcement?", options:{A:"It diverts FRSC funding to other departments",B:"It allows violators to pay bribes instead of facing prosecution",C:"It prevents the construction of new roads",D:"It encourages foreign investors to avoid Nigeria"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The passage states corruption 'allows violators to pay bribes rather than face prosecution,' undermining the FRSC's enforcement role. This is explicitly stated in the second paragraph." },
      { id:"en5_9", question:"The phrase 'binding constraint' as used in the passage means:", options:{A:"A legal restriction imposed by courts",B:"The most critical factor limiting progress",C:"A physical barrier on Nigerian roads",D:"An international agreement limiting funding"}, answer:"B", explanation:"A binding constraint in economics and policy means the single most limiting factor, the one that, if removed, would unlock progress. Experts argue political will, not resources, is this key limiting factor. The word binding = most restrictive." },
      { id:"en5_10", question:"What is the writer's main recommendation for solving Nigeria's road safety crisis?", options:{A:"A single large investment in new roads",B:"International aid to purchase new vehicles",C:"An integrated response covering infrastructure, vehicles, licensing, and accountability",D:"The replacement of the FRSC with a new agency"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The final paragraph lists multiple components: infrastructure upgrade, vehicle certification, reformed licensing, and a culture of accountability. The writer's position is explicitly integrated and multi-pronged, not a single intervention." }
    ]
  },

  // -- CLOZE TEST --
  {
    section: "Cloze Test",
    passage: `Nigeria's agricultural sector, despite its enormous (11)___, contributes less to GDP than it should. The country is (12)___ with fertile land, reliable rainfall in many regions, and a large rural labour force. Yet poor rural infrastructure, (13)___ access to credit, and post-harvest losses continue to (14)___ the potential of millions of smallholder farmers. Government (15)___ to bridge this gap have been inconsistent. Subsidy schemes that were (16)___ to reach the poorest farmers have often been (17)___ by politically connected middlemen. (18)___, technology is beginning to offer new hope. Mobile applications that connect farmers directly to markets are (19)___ the role of exploitative middlemen and helping farmers obtain (20)___ prices for their produce.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_11", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 11.", options:{A:"limitations",B:"potential",C:"failures",D:"bureaucracy"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The sentence contrasts what the sector has (enormous potential) with what it actually contributes. The word potential fits the contrast established by despite. Limitations or failures would make the despite clause redundant." },
      { id:"en5_12", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 12.", options:{A:"struggling",B:"familiar",C:"endowed",D:"challenged"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Endowed with means naturally provided with or blessed with. Nigeria is endowed with fertile land, rainfall, and labour. This is the standard collocating expression. Struggling or challenged would contradict the positive listing that follows." },
      { id:"en5_13", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 13.", options:{A:"excess",B:"limited",C:"rapid",D:"equal"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The sentence lists obstacles: poor infrastructure, limited access to credit, and post-harvest losses. Limited access to credit is the established phrase for financial exclusion faced by smallholder farmers." },
      { id:"en5_14", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 14.", options:{A:"expand",B:"celebrate",C:"undermine",D:"replace"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The gap continues the listing of obstacles. Undermine means to weaken or damage progressively. The poor conditions undermine the potential of farmers, damaging what could be achieved. Expand would be the opposite meaning." },
      { id:"en5_15", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 15.", options:{A:"attempts",B:"failures",C:"arrests",D:"exports"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Government attempts to bridge this gap is the natural expression. The following sentence explains why those attempts have been inconsistent. Failures is possible but anticipates the criticism rather than neutrally introducing it." },
      { id:"en5_16", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 16.", options:{A:"designed",B:"forbidden",C:"renamed",D:"exported"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Subsidy schemes that were designed to reach the poorest farmers is the correct construction. Designed to means intended to. The contrast is between the design intention and the corrupt reality." },
      { id:"en5_17", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 17.", options:{A:"distributed",B:"hijacked",C:"repaired",D:"monitored"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Hijacked by politically connected middlemen means seized and diverted for private gain. This fits the corruption context perfectly. Schemes designed for the poor were hijacked (stolen/redirected) by the politically connected." },
      { id:"en5_18", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 18.", options:{A:"However",B:"Therefore",C:"Similarly",D:"Unless"}, answer:"A", explanation:"However introduces a contrasting idea. The previous sentences describe failure and corruption; however signals a positive turn: technology is beginning to offer new hope. However = despite the above, something positive is happening." },
      { id:"en5_19", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 19.", options:{A:"strengthening",B:"ignoring",C:"eliminating",D:"funding"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Mobile apps connect farmers directly to markets, eliminating (removing) the role of exploitative middlemen. Eliminating is the action that matches the direct connection: if farmers sell directly, the middleman's role is removed." },
      { id:"en5_20", question:"Choose the word that best fills gap 20.", options:{A:"lower",B:"fairer",C:"slower",D:"foreign"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Farmers obtaining fairer prices for their produce is the natural conclusion. Fairer means more equitable, more in line with market value. Lower prices would be a negative outcome for farmers, contradicting the hopeful tone." }
    ]
  },

  // -- LEXIS AND STRUCTURE --
  {
    section: "Lexis & Structure",
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_21", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to OSTENTATIOUS.", options:{A:"Modest",B:"Showy and designed to impress",C:"Secretive",D:"Exhausted"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Ostentatious means excessively showy, done to attract attention and impress others. From Latin ostentare (to show off). Example: an ostentatious display of wealth. The opposite is modest or understated." },
      { id:"en5_22", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to UBIQUITOUS.", options:{A:"Rare and unusual",B:"Dangerous",C:"Present or appearing everywhere",D:"Difficult to understand"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Ubiquitous means present, appearing, or found everywhere. From Latin ubique (everywhere). Example: Mobile phones are ubiquitous in modern Nigeria. The opposite is rare or scarce." },
      { id:"en5_23", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to MENDACIOUS.", options:{A:"Truthful",B:"Dishonest and given to lying",C:"Generous",D:"Cautious"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Mendacious means not telling the truth, habitually lying. From Latin mendax (lying). A mendacious politician makes false promises. The noun is mendacity. The opposite is veracious or truthful." },
      { id:"en5_24", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to FRUGAL.", options:{A:"Careful",B:"Poor",C:"Extravagant",D:"Honest"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Frugal means careful and sparing in the use of money or food. Its opposite is extravagant (spending much more than necessary). Do not confuse with poor (lacking money) or stingy (unwilling to spend). Frugal is a positive quality; stingy is negative." },
      { id:"en5_25", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to BELLIGERENT.", options:{A:"Aggressive",B:"Peaceful",C:"Loud",D:"Dishonest"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Belligerent means hostile and aggressive, inclined to quarrel or fight. Its antonym is peaceful or pacific. Aggressive is a synonym, not an antonym. Example: a belligerent nation is one eager for conflict." },
      { id:"en5_26", question:"What does the idiom 'the ball is in your court' mean?", options:{A:"You are playing a sport",B:"It is now your responsibility or decision to act",C:"You have won the competition",D:"You have made a serious mistake"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The ball is in your court means it is now up to you to take the next action or make the decision. From tennis, where the ball being in your court means you must now hit it. Example: I have made my offer; the ball is in your court." },
      { id:"en5_27", question:"What does the idiom 'spill the beans' mean?", options:{A:"To make a mess carelessly",B:"To reveal a secret accidentally or without permission",C:"To cook a meal hastily",D:"To waste food resources"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Spill the beans means to accidentally or prematurely reveal confidential information. Example: She spilled the beans about the surprise party before it happened. The origin is disputed but the meaning is well established." },
      { id:"en5_28", question:"Choose the sentence with the correct use of the SUBJUNCTIVE mood:", options:{A:"If he was here, he would help us",B:"She suggested that he goes to the office immediately",C:"I wish she was more careful with her words",D:"The committee recommends that the director resign immediately"}, answer:"D", explanation:"The subjunctive mood is used after verbs of recommendation, suggestion, demand, and request: recommend that + base verb (resign, not resigns). Option D is correct. Options A and C should use were (subjunctive), not was. Option B should use go, not goes." },
      { id:"en5_29", question:"Identify the ACTIVE voice equivalent of: 'The letter was written by the secretary.'", options:{A:"The letter has been written by the secretary",B:"The secretary wrote the letter",C:"The letter will be written by the secretary",D:"The letter is written by the secretary"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Active voice: Subject + verb + object. The secretary (subject) wrote (verb) the letter (object). The original passive has the letter as grammatical subject with the agent (secretary) in a by-phrase. Active voice places the agent as the subject." },
      { id:"en5_30", question:"Choose the correct form: 'Neither of the students ___ submitted the assignment.'", options:{A:"have",B:"has",C:"are",D:"were"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Neither takes a singular verb when used as a pronoun. Neither of the students has (singular) submitted. This is a standard JAMB trap. Compare: neither A nor B - verb agrees with B. But neither of [plural noun] always takes singular." },
      { id:"en5_31", question:"Identify the figure of speech in: 'The classroom was a zoo during the teacher's absence.'", options:{A:"Simile",B:"Hyperbole",C:"Metaphor",D:"Alliteration"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The classroom is directly called a zoo (not like a zoo). Direct comparison without like or as is a METAPHOR. A simile would say the classroom was LIKE a zoo. The comparison implies the students behaved wildly." },
      { id:"en5_32", question:"Identify the figure of speech in: 'I have told you a million times to close that door.'", options:{A:"Metaphor",B:"Irony",C:"Hyperbole",D:"Personification"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Hyperbole is deliberate and obvious exaggeration for emphasis or effect, not meant to be taken literally. A million times is an exaggeration to emphasise frustration. No one literally says something a million times." },
      { id:"en5_33", question:"Identify the figure of speech in: 'The stars danced in the night sky.'", options:{A:"Simile",B:"Metaphor",C:"Alliteration",D:"Personification"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Personification attributes human characteristics or actions to non-human things. Stars cannot literally dance; dancing is a human action attributed to the stars. This gives the night sky a lively, animate quality." },
      { id:"en5_34", question:"Choose the sentence with the correct use of 'who' and 'whom':", options:{A:"Who did you call yesterday?",B:"Whom is responsible for this error?",C:"The man who I spoke to was helpful",D:"The student whom scored highest was awarded"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Who = subject pronoun; whom = object pronoun. In 'Who did you call?' the understood structure is 'You did call who?' where who is the object, BUT in informal registers JAMB accepts who. More precisely: 'Whom did you call?' is most formal. Among the options, A is the most commonly acceptable form in JAMB. B should be Who; D should be who." },
      { id:"en5_35", question:"Choose the correct sentence:", options:{A:"Hardly had she arrived when the meeting began",B:"Hardly she had arrived when the meeting began",C:"Hardly had she arrived than the meeting began",D:"Hardly she had arrived before the meeting began"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Hardly...when is the correct paired conjunction for this inversion structure. When the negative adverb Hardly begins the sentence, subject-auxiliary inversion occurs: Hardly had she + past participle. The connector is when, not than (that would be No sooner...than)." },
      { id:"en5_36", question:"What is the function of the underlined word in: 'Running every morning keeps him healthy'?", options:{A:"It is a present participle",B:"It is a gerund acting as the subject of the sentence",C:"It is an infinitive",D:"It is an adverb"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Running every morning is a gerund phrase acting as the SUBJECT of the sentence (it keeps = what keeps him healthy). A gerund is a verb+ing form functioning as a noun. As subject, it can take the verb keeps. A present participle would modify a noun." },
      { id:"en5_37", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to NONCHALANT.", options:{A:"Excited",B:"Casually calm and unconcerned",C:"Hostile",D:"Formal"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Nonchalant means feeling or appearing casually calm and relaxed, not displaying anxiety or enthusiasm. From French non chaloir (not to be concerned). Example: She gave a nonchalant shrug when told her results." },
      { id:"en5_38", question:"Choose the correct option: 'Each of the boys ___ given a prize.'", options:{A:"were",B:"are",C:"was",D:"have been"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Each is always singular in standard English grammar. Each of the boys was (singular, past) given a prize. This is one of the most common JAMB concord traps. Each, every, either, neither, anyone, everyone all take singular verbs." },
      { id:"en5_39", question:"What does 'propitious' mean?", options:{A:"Unfortunate and ill-timed",B:"Favourable and giving a good chance of success",C:"Angry and confrontational",D:"Overly polite"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Propitious means giving or indicating a good chance of success, favourable. Example: a propitious moment to launch the business. The opposite is inauspicious or unpropitious. Not to be confused with propitious (not propitiate = to appease)." },
      { id:"en5_40", question:"Choose the sentence that correctly uses the PAST PERFECT tense:", options:{A:"She had already left before I arrived",B:"She already left before I arrived",C:"She has already left before I arrived",D:"She was already left before I arrived"}, answer:"A", explanation:"The past perfect (had + past participle) is used for an action completed BEFORE another past action. She had already left (earlier action) before I arrived (later past action). Option B uses simple past; C uses present perfect incorrectly; D is grammatically wrong." }
    ]
  },

  // -- ORAL ENGLISH --
  {
    section: "Oral English",
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_41", question:"In which word is the vowel sound /i:/ (as in 'see') heard?", options:{A:"Sit",B:"Set",C:"Seat",D:"Soot"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Seat contains the long vowel /i:/ as in see, feet, beat. Sit contains the short vowel /I/. Set contains /e/. Soot contains /u/ or /U/. The distinction between short /I/ (sit) and long /i:/ (seat) is one of the most tested vowel pairs in JAMB." },
      { id:"en5_42", question:"Which word has the stress on the SECOND syllable?", options:{A:"PREsent (noun)",B:"reCORD (verb)",C:"PROtest (noun)",D:"INsult (noun)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Record as a VERB = re-CORD (stress on second syllable). Record as a NOUN = RE-cord (stress on first syllable). This is the noun/verb stress shift pattern. Similarly: present, protest, insult, import, export, permit, refuse all shift stress from first (noun) to second (verb)." },
      { id:"en5_43", question:"Which word contains the sound /dZ/ (as in 'judge')?", options:{A:"Chair",B:"Show",C:"Gym",D:"King"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Gym begins with /dZ/ (the voiced affricate, same sound as the g in giant, gene, giraffe). Chair begins with /tS/ (voiceless affricate). Show begins with /S/ (fricative). King ends with /N/ (nasal). The /dZ/ sound is spelled as j, g (before e/i/y), or dge." },
      { id:"en5_44", question:"How many syllables does the word PARTICULARLY have?", options:{A:"4",B:"5",C:"6",D:"3"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Particularly: par-TIC-u-lar-ly = 5 syllables. The stress falls on the second syllable: par-TIC-u-lar-ly. Counting syllables: every syllable contains exactly one vowel sound. Avoid conflating spelling with pronunciation." },
      { id:"en5_45", question:"Which pair of words are HOMOPHONES (same pronunciation, different spelling)?", options:{A:"Bear and beer",B:"Sea and see",C:"Lead (metal) and lead (to guide)",D:"Flour and flower are not homophones"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Homophones are words pronounced the same but spelled differently and meaning different things. Sea /si:/ and see /si:/ are perfect homophones. Bear /beE/ and beer /bIE/ are NOT homophones. Lead (metal) = /led/ and lead (guide) = /li:d/ are NOT homophones." },
      { id:"en5_46", question:"Where does the primary stress fall in the word EXAMINATION?", options:{A:"ex-AM-i-na-tion",B:"ex-am-i-NA-tion",C:"EX-am-i-na-tion",D:"ex-am-I-na-tion"}, answer:"B", explanation:"EXAMINATION: ex-am-i-NA-tion. The stress falls on the fourth syllable (-NA-). Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ation, -ician carry primary stress on the syllable immediately before the suffix. Examples: examiNAtion, communicAtion, educAtion." },
      { id:"en5_47", question:"Which word contains the consonant sound /T/ (as in 'think')?", options:{A:"This",B:"Those",C:"Thunder",D:"Though"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Thunder contains the voiceless dental fricative /T/ as in think, tooth, through. This, Those, and Though all contain the VOICED dental fricative /D/ as in the, them, there. The distinction between /T/ (voiceless) and /D/ (voiced) is critical in JAMB oral English." },
      { id:"en5_48", question:"In which word is the letter 'g' SILENT?", options:{A:"Grab",B:"Gnome",C:"Glow",D:"Grape"}, answer:"B", explanation:"In gnome, the initial g is silent: pronounced /noUm/. Silent g appears in words beginning with gn: gnome, gnu, gnaw, gnash. In grab, glow, and grape, the g is pronounced. This silent consonant pattern is regularly tested in JAMB." },
      { id:"en5_49", question:"What is the correct pronunciation stress for the word ECONOMICS?", options:{A:"e-CO-no-mics",B:"e-co-NO-mics",C:"E-co-no-mics",D:"e-co-no-MICS"}, answer:"B", explanation:"ECONOMICS: e-co-NO-mics. The stress falls on the third syllable. This is part of the -nomics family: ecoNOMics, agroNOMy, asTRONomy. JAMB frequently tests stress in words from social science and academic vocabulary." },
      { id:"en5_50", question:"Which sentence demonstrates FALLING intonation on a Wh-question?", options:{A:"Are you coming to school tomorrow?",B:"Where is the examination centre?",C:"Is that your bag?",D:"Has she arrived yet?"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Wh-questions (who, what, where, when, why, how) typically use FALLING intonation in English because the speaker expects a definite answer. Yes/No questions (A, C, D) typically use RISING intonation because the answer is open. This is a fundamental intonation pattern tested in JAMB." }
    ]
  },

  // -- NOVEL: THE LEKKI HEADMASTER --
  {
    section: "Novel - The Lekki Headmaster",
    questions: [
      { id:"en5_51", question:"What is Beke Egbin's role in Stardom Schools?", options:{A:"Vice-Principal",B:"School Counsellor",C:"Head of English Department",D:"School Proprietor"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Beke Egbin serves as the school counsellor at Stardom Schools. In the novel, counsellors like Beke represent the pastoral and emotional support structure of the school, contrasting with the administrative authority of Bepo and Mrs. Apeh." },
      { id:"en5_52", question:"Bepo's wife Seri is established in the novel as:", options:{A:"A retired teacher living in Lagos",B:"A nurse working in the United Kingdom",C:"A businesswoman based in Abuja",D:"A university lecturer in Nigeria"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Seri (Mr. Adebepo Adewale's wife) is a nurse working in the United Kingdom. Her presence abroad creates the personal dimension of Bepo's dilemma: staying in Nigeria means prolonged separation from his family." },
      { id:"en5_53", question:"Bepo's two daughters Nike and Kike are established as living:", options:{A:"In Lagos with their grandmother",B:"In Abuja attending university",C:"In the United Kingdom with their mother",D:"Abroad independently of both parents"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Nike and Kike, Bepo's daughters, live in the United Kingdom with their mother Seri. Their absence from Nigeria is part of the emotional and family dimension of Bepo's conflict between duty to his country and reunion with his family." },
      { id:"en5_54", question:"The title 'The Lekki Headmaster' is significant primarily because:", options:{A:"It refers to a historical figure who founded Lekki",B:"It establishes the geographical and professional context of the protagonist's dilemma",C:"It suggests the novel is a detective story set in Lekki",D:"Lekki is the setting of the school's annual sports day"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The title combines geography (Lekki, a prosperous part of Lagos) with professional identity (headmaster/principal). This immediately establishes the tension: a school leader in one of Nigeria's wealthiest areas who still cannot afford to keep his family together." },
      { id:"en5_55", question:"Stardom Schools is described in the novel as being located in:", options:{A:"Abuja, the Federal Capital Territory",B:"Ibadan, Oyo State",C:"Lekki, Lagos",D:"Enugu, Enugu State"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Stardom Schools is located in Lekki, Lagos. The choice of Lekki, an affluent coastal suburb, is thematically significant: it places Bepo in proximity to Nigeria's wealthy elite while he himself struggles on a teacher's salary." },
      { id:"en5_56", question:"How long has Bepo worked at Stardom Schools by the time the novel's main action takes place?", options:{A:"10 years",B:"15 years",C:"24 years",D:"30 years"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Bepo has worked at Stardom Schools for 24 years. This long tenure underscores the depth of his commitment and sacrifice. It also intensifies the dilemma: after 24 years of service, his decision to leave or stay carries enormous weight." },
      { id:"en5_57", question:"The theme of 'japa' in the novel refers to:", options:{A:"A traditional Yoruba ceremony celebrated in the school",B:"The Nigerian slang for emigrating abroad in search of better opportunities",C:"The name of a competing school in Lekki",D:"Bepo's nickname among his students"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Japa is contemporary Nigerian slang (from Yoruba) meaning to flee or run away, now widely used to describe emigrating abroad for better economic prospects. The novel engages directly with this modern Nigerian phenomenon, using Bepo's situation to examine its moral and patriotic implications." },
      { id:"en5_58", question:"The novel's setting in a PRIVATE school (rather than a public one) is significant because it:", options:{A:"Suggests Bepo is already wealthy and has no reason to leave",B:"Shows that even well-positioned educators in Nigeria face inadequate compensation",C:"Implies the novel is unconcerned with public education",D:"Indicates Bepo has political connections"}, answer:"B", explanation:"By setting the novel in a private school in wealthy Lekki, the author makes a pointed argument: even teachers at elite private institutions in Nigeria's richest neighbourhood are inadequately compensated. This makes the economic pressure to emigrate universal, not just a public sector problem." },
      { id:"en5_59", question:"The recurring motif of Bepo looking out of his office window at the school compound primarily symbolises:", options:{A:"His boredom with his administrative role",B:"His surveillance of student behaviour",C:"His deep attachment to the institution and what it represents",D:"His desire to escape the school physically"}, answer:"C", explanation:"In the novel, Bepo's gaze across his school compound is a recurring symbol of ownership, pride, and attachment. It represents what he would be leaving behind: not just a job, but an institution he has helped build over 24 years. The window becomes a symbol of his torn loyalty." },
      { id:"en5_60", question:"Which statement best captures the novel's resolution?", options:{A:"Bepo accepts the overseas position and emigrates with his family",B:"Bepo is dismissed from Stardom Schools before he can decide",C:"Bepo chooses to remain in Nigeria out of duty to his students and country",D:"Bepo retires and is replaced by Mrs. Grace Apeh"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The novel's resolution is Bepo's decision to remain in Nigeria, driven by his sense of patriotic duty and his bond with his students. This ending affirms the novel's central thesis: that Nigeria's future depends on committed citizens choosing to stay and build rather than flee." }
    ]
  }

]; // end Use of English[5]

DB["Biology"][5] = [
  { id:"bi5_1", question:"Which of the following correctly describes the structure of DNA according to the Watson-Crick model?", options:{A:"Single-stranded helix with bases projecting outward",B:"Double helix with sugar-phosphate backbones on the outside and paired bases on the inside",C:"Double helix with bases on the outside and sugar-phosphate backbone on the inside",D:"Triple helix stabilised by hydrogen bonds between three strands"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Watson and Crick (1953): DNA is a double helix. Sugar-phosphate backbones form the outside rails; bases point inward and pair by hydrogen bonds (A with T; G with C). This antiparallel structure (one strand runs 5'to3', the other 3'to5') is fundamental to replication and transcription." },
  { id:"bi5_2", question:"During DNA replication, the enzyme responsible for synthesising new DNA strands is:", options:{A:"Helicase",B:"DNA ligase",C:"DNA polymerase III",D:"Primase"}, answer:"C", explanation:"DNA polymerase III (in prokaryotes) synthesises the new DNA strand by adding nucleotides 5' to 3'. Helicase unwinds the double helix. Primase synthesises the RNA primer. DNA ligase joins Okazaki fragments. Each enzyme has a distinct, sequential role." },
  { id:"bi5_3", question:"Which of the following is the CORRECT base-pairing rule for DNA?", options:{A:"Adenine pairs with Cytosine; Guanine pairs with Thymine",B:"Adenine pairs with Guanine; Cytosine pairs with Thymine",C:"Adenine pairs with Thymine; Guanine pairs with Cytosine",D:"Adenine pairs with Uracil; Guanine pairs with Cytosine"}, answer:"C", explanation:"In DNA: A pairs with T (2 hydrogen bonds); G pairs with C (3 hydrogen bonds). A-U pairing occurs in RNA, not DNA. The rule ensures the double helix maintains constant width: a purine (A or G) always pairs with a pyrimidine (T or C)." },
  { id:"bi5_4", question:"mRNA is transcribed from the template strand of DNA. If the DNA template strand reads 3'-TACGCA-5', what is the mRNA sequence?", options:{A:"3'-AUGCGU-5'",B:"5'-AUGCGU-3'",C:"5'-TACGCA-3'",D:"5'-UACGCA-3'"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Transcription: mRNA is synthesised 5' to 3' complementary to the 3' to 5' template strand, replacing T with U. Template 3'-TACGCA-5' gives mRNA 5'-AUGCGU-3'. Check: T->A(->U in mRNA); A->U; C->G; G->C; C->G; A->U. Answer = AUGCGU read 5' to 3'." },
  { id:"bi5_5", question:"In translation, which molecule carries the amino acid to the ribosome?", options:{A:"mRNA",B:"rRNA",C:"tRNA",D:"DNA"}, answer:"C", explanation:"tRNA (transfer RNA): each tRNA molecule carries a specific amino acid at its 3' end and has an anticodon loop that base-pairs with the mRNA codon. mRNA carries the genetic message; rRNA is a structural component of ribosomes; DNA is not directly involved in translation." },
  { id:"bi5_6", question:"The lymphatic system returns excess tissue fluid to the blood by draining into the:", options:{A:"Right ventricle of the heart",B:"Hepatic portal vein",C:"Subclavian veins via the thoracic duct and right lymphatic duct",D:"Left atrium of the heart"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The thoracic duct (draining left side and lower body) and right lymphatic duct (draining upper right) empty lymph into the subclavian veins. This returns the fluid to the venous circulation before it enters the right heart. Lymph never enters the heart directly." },
  { id:"bi5_7", question:"Which component of blood is responsible for clotting?", options:{A:"Erythrocytes",B:"Lymphocytes",C:"Platelets (thrombocytes)",D:"Monocytes"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Platelets (thrombocytes) are cell fragments that aggregate at wound sites and initiate the clotting cascade, ultimately producing fibrin to seal the wound. Erythrocytes carry O2. Lymphocytes and monocytes are white blood cells involved in immunity, not clotting." },
  { id:"bi5_8", question:"Where does the exchange of gases between the blood and tissues occur?", options:{A:"Arteries",B:"Arterioles",C:"Capillaries",D:"Venules"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Capillaries have walls only one cell thick (single endothelium layer), allowing O2, CO2, nutrients, and waste to diffuse between blood and interstitial fluid. Arteries and arterioles are thick-walled and carry blood under high pressure away from the heart. Venules collect from capillaries." },
  { id:"bi5_9", question:"Haemoglobin's oxygen dissociation curve shifts to the RIGHT in the presence of higher CO2 and lower pH. This means:", options:{A:"Haemoglobin binds oxygen more tightly",B:"Haemoglobin releases oxygen more readily to active tissues",C:"Haemoglobin transports more oxygen at any given partial pressure",D:"Carbon dioxide replaces oxygen on haemoglobin permanently"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The Bohr effect: higher CO2 and lower pH (as in active, metabolising tissues) shift the dissociation curve right, lowering Hb's affinity for O2 and causing it to release O2 more readily. This delivers more O2 precisely where it is most needed." },
  { id:"bi5_10", question:"The bicuspid (mitral) valve is located between:", options:{A:"Right atrium and right ventricle",B:"Left ventricle and the aorta",C:"Left atrium and left ventricle",D:"Right ventricle and the pulmonary artery"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Bicuspid (mitral) valve: between LEFT atrium and LEFT ventricle. Tricuspid valve: between right atrium and right ventricle. Semilunar valves: between ventricles and great arteries. Knowing left from right sides is essential for heart anatomy questions." },
  { id:"bi5_11", question:"What distinguishes a MOTOR (efferent) neuron structurally from a SENSORY (afferent) neuron?", options:{A:"Motor neurons lack a myelin sheath",B:"Sensory neurons have a cell body far from the spinal cord",C:"Motor neurons have a long axon carrying impulses from the CNS to effectors; sensory neurons carry impulses to the CNS",D:"Motor neurons are always unmyelinated; sensory neurons are myelinated"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Motor (efferent) neurons: cell body in CNS, long axon to effectors (muscles/glands). Sensory (afferent) neurons: receptor in periphery, cell body in dorsal root ganglion, carry impulses TO CNS. Both can be myelinated. The key distinction is direction: sensory = to CNS; motor = from CNS." },
  { id:"bi5_12", question:"The knee-jerk (patellar) reflex is an example of a:", options:{A:"Conditioned reflex involving the cerebrum",B:"Cranial reflex processed in the medulla oblongata",C:"Spinal reflex that does NOT pass through the brain",D:"Hormonal response mediated by the adrenal gland"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The patellar reflex arc: hammer strikes patellar tendon, stretch receptor fires, sensory neuron to spinal cord, relay neuron, motor neuron to quadriceps. The brain receives information but is NOT part of the arc. This is a monosynaptic spinal reflex." },
  { id:"bi5_13", question:"Which hormone is produced by the islets of Langerhans in the ALPHA cells of the pancreas?", options:{A:"Insulin",B:"Glucagon",C:"Adrenaline",D:"Cortisol"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Alpha cells of the islets of Langerhans produce GLUCAGON, which raises blood glucose by stimulating glycogenolysis in the liver. Beta cells produce INSULIN, which lowers blood glucose. Adrenaline comes from the adrenal medulla; cortisol from the adrenal cortex." },
  { id:"bi5_14", question:"Which of the following correctly describes NEGATIVE FEEDBACK in blood glucose regulation?", options:{A:"Rising glucose triggers glucagon release which raises glucose further",B:"Rising glucose triggers insulin release which lowers glucose back to normal",C:"Falling glucose triggers insulin release which raises glucose",D:"Rising glucose triggers both insulin and glucagon simultaneously"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Negative feedback: the output (rising blood glucose) triggers a response (insulin release) that OPPOSES the change (lowers glucose back toward the set point). This maintains homeostasis. Positive feedback would amplify the change rather than reverse it." },
  { id:"bi5_15", question:"The menstrual cycle is regulated by a hormonal feedback loop. Which event correctly describes mid-cycle?", options:{A:"Progesterone peaks, causing ovulation",B:"FSH peaks, directly causing menstruation",C:"An LH surge triggers ovulation on approximately day 14",D:"Oestrogen falls to zero, triggering follicle development"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Mid-cycle (around day 14): oestrogen rises sharply as the Graafian follicle develops, triggering a positive feedback LH surge that causes ovulation. Post-ovulation, the corpus luteum produces progesterone which (negative feedback) suppresses FSH and LH." },
  { id:"bi5_16", question:"Which of the following is an example of MUTUALISM?", options:{A:"A tapeworm living inside the intestine of a host",B:"Remora fish attached to a shark",C:"Rhizobium bacteria living in legume root nodules",D:"A tick feeding on a dog"}, answer:"C", explanation:"MUTUALISM: both partners benefit. Rhizobium fixes atmospheric N2 into ammonia that the legume uses; the legume provides carbohydrates and a protected environment. Tapeworm and tick are PARASITISM (one benefits, host is harmed). Remora is COMMENSALISM (one benefits, host neither harmed nor helped)." },
  { id:"bi5_17", question:"In an ecosystem, which trophic level contains the LEAST energy?", options:{A:"Producers",B:"Primary consumers",C:"Secondary consumers",D:"Tertiary consumers"}, answer:"D", explanation:"The 10% rule: only about 10% of energy is transferred between trophic levels (the rest is lost as heat, used in metabolism, or in indigestible material). Tertiary consumers are the highest level shown, receiving only 0.1% of the original producer energy. Producers contain the most energy." },
  { id:"bi5_18", question:"Which biome is characterised by permafrost, low precipitation, and dominant vegetation of mosses, lichens, and dwarf shrubs?", options:{A:"Tropical rainforest",B:"Temperate grassland (savanna)",C:"Boreal forest (taiga)",D:"Tundra"}, answer:"D", explanation:"TUNDRA: found in Arctic and alpine regions; permanently frozen subsoil (permafrost) prevents tree growth; dominant plants are mosses, lichens, sedges, and dwarf shrubs. Taiga has coniferous trees. Savanna has grasses and scattered trees. Tropical rainforest has maximum biodiversity and rainfall." },
  { id:"bi5_19", question:"Which of the following best defines BIODIVERSITY?", options:{A:"The total mass of all living organisms in an ecosystem",B:"The number of trophic levels in a food web",C:"The variety of life at genetic, species, and ecosystem levels",D:"The rate of energy flow through an ecosystem"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Biodiversity has THREE components: (1) genetic diversity (variation within species); (2) species diversity (number and abundance of species); (3) ecosystem diversity (variety of habitats and ecological processes). Biomass is productivity; trophic levels describe food web structure." },
  { id:"bi5_20", question:"In Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection, which statement is CORRECT?", options:{A:"Individuals evolve during their lifetime to suit their environment",B:"Populations evolve over generations as individuals with favourable heritable variations survive and reproduce more",C:"Evolution requires a directed goal toward which species are progressing",D:"All mutations are beneficial and drive evolution forward"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Natural selection acts on POPULATIONS, not individuals. Individuals do not evolve; populations change over generations. Variation is heritable; those with favourable variations survive and reproduce more (differential reproductive success), passing traits to offspring. Most mutations are neutral or harmful." },
  { id:"bi5_21", question:"The Hardy-Weinberg principle states that allele frequencies in a population remain CONSTANT unless:", options:{A:"The population is large and no migration occurs",B:"One of five conditions is violated: non-random mating, mutation, genetic drift, gene flow, or natural selection",C:"Mutation rate exceeds reproduction rate",D:"The population is isolated on an island"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires: (1) large population; (2) random mating; (3) no mutation; (4) no migration (gene flow); (5) no natural selection. Violation of ANY of these causes allele frequencies to change, driving evolution." },
  { id:"bi5_22", question:"Which of the following is an example of DISRUPTIVE selection?", options:{A:"Average-sized individuals survive best in a stable environment",B:"Extremely large OR extremely small individuals survive better than average ones",C:"The largest individuals consistently outcompete all others",D:"Environmental change causes all individuals to become medium-sized"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Disruptive (diversifying) selection favours both extremes over the intermediate phenotype, potentially splitting a population into two groups. Stabilising selection favours the intermediate phenotype. Directional selection shifts the population toward one extreme." },
  { id:"bi5_23", question:"What is the role of the Golgi apparatus in a cell?", options:{A:"Site of ATP production via oxidative phosphorylation",B:"Processing, packaging, and dispatching proteins and lipids to their destinations",C:"Synthesis of proteins on ribosomes",D:"Storage of genetic information in the form of DNA"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The Golgi apparatus (Golgi body): receives proteins from the ER, modifies them (glycosylation, phosphorylation), sorts them, and packages them into vesicles for secretion, lysosomes, or the plasma membrane. It is the cell's post office and processing centre." },
  { id:"bi5_24", question:"During aerobic respiration, in which organelle does the Krebs cycle take place?", options:{A:"Nucleus",B:"Cytoplasm",C:"Mitochondrial matrix",D:"Inner mitochondrial membrane"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Krebs cycle (citric acid cycle): occurs in the MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX. Pyruvate is first converted to acetyl-CoA in the matrix. The electron transport chain (ETC) occurs on the INNER MITOCHONDRIAL MEMBRANE. Glycolysis occurs in the CYTOPLASM." },
  { id:"bi5_25", question:"Which photosynthesis reaction produces ATP, NADPH, and O2?", options:{A:"Calvin cycle (dark reactions)",B:"Photorespiration",C:"Light-dependent reactions",D:"Glycolysis"}, answer:"C", explanation:"LIGHT-DEPENDENT REACTIONS (thylakoid membranes): light energy splits water (photolysis) releasing O2; excited electrons flow through the ETC producing ATP (by photophosphorylation) and NADPH. These products fuel the Calvin cycle. The Calvin cycle produces G3P using ATP and NADPH." },
  { id:"bi5_26", question:"In a dihybrid cross between two heterozygotes (AaBb × AaBb), assuming independent assortment, what ratio of offspring show BOTH dominant phenotypes?", options:{A:"3:1",B:"9:7",C:"1:2:1",D:"9:3:3:1 so 9 out of 16"}, answer:"D", explanation:"AaBb × AaBb: standard dihybrid ratio 9:3:3:1. Those showing BOTH dominant phenotypes = A_B_ = 9/16. Those showing only dominant A = 3/16; only dominant B = 3/16; both recessive = 1/16. The probability of each dominant phenotype = 3/4, so together = 3/4 × 3/4 = 9/16." },
  { id:"bi5_27", question:"What type of inheritance is exhibited when a cross of red-flowered and white-flowered plants produces only PINK-flowered F1 offspring?", options:{A:"Complete dominance",B:"Co-dominance",C:"Incomplete dominance",D:"Epistasis"}, answer:"C", explanation:"INCOMPLETE DOMINANCE: neither allele is fully dominant; the heterozygote (F1) shows an intermediate phenotype (pink = blend of red and white). CO-DOMINANCE: both alleles are fully expressed (e.g., ABO blood group AB), not blended. Complete dominance: one allele fully masks the other." },
  { id:"bi5_28", question:"Which of the following is a VESTIGIAL structure in humans?", options:{A:"The appendix and coccyx",B:"The femur and tibia",C:"The cerebral cortex",D:"The cardiac muscle"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Vestigial structures are reduced, non-functional (or minimally functional) remnants of structures that had greater importance in ancestral organisms. The coccyx (remnant of a tail) and appendix (remnant of a cecal digestive structure) are classic human vestigial structures, evidence of evolution." },
  { id:"bi5_29", question:"Which of the following organisms is classified in the Kingdom Fungi?", options:{A:"Spirogyra",B:"Rhizopus (bread mould)",C:"Chlamydomonas",D:"Euglena"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Rhizopus (black bread mould) is a fungus: heterotrophic, cell walls of chitin, no chlorophyll, reproduces by spores. Spirogyra and Chlamydomonas are green algae (Kingdom Protista or Plantae depending on classification). Euglena is a flagellated protist." },
  { id:"bi5_30", question:"What is the primary function of the mammalian liver in metabolism?", options:{A:"Production of digestive enzymes for the small intestine",B:"Filtration of blood to remove bacteria",C:"Regulation of blood glucose, detoxification, production of bile, and deamination of amino acids",D:"Production of red blood cells in adults"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The liver is the metabolic hub: (1) glycogenesis/glycogenolysis to regulate blood glucose; (2) deamination of amino acids and urea production; (3) bile production for fat emulsification; (4) detoxification of drugs and alcohol; (5) storage of vitamins A, D, B12, iron. It has over 500 known functions." },
  { id:"bi5_31", question:"Which structure prevents food from entering the trachea during swallowing?", options:{A:"Uvula",B:"Epiglottis",C:"Vocal cords",D:"Soft palate"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The EPIGLOTTIS is a flap of cartilage at the base of the tongue that folds over the glottis (opening of the trachea) during swallowing, directing food into the oesophagus. When it fails momentarily, food enters the trachea, causing choking. The uvula separates oral and nasal cavities." },
  { id:"bi5_32", question:"The term OSMOSIS refers to:", options:{A:"The movement of solute molecules from high to low concentration through a membrane",B:"The net movement of WATER molecules from a region of higher water potential to lower water potential through a selectively permeable membrane",C:"Active transport of ions against a concentration gradient",D:"Bulk flow of water under pressure through xylem vessels"}, answer:"B", explanation:"OSMOSIS: passive movement of WATER only, through a selectively permeable membrane, from high water potential (low solute) to low water potential (high solute). Solute movement is diffusion; ion movement against gradient is active transport; xylem flow is mass flow." },
  { id:"bi5_33", question:"In transpiration, which factor would MOST increase the rate of water loss from leaves?", options:{A:"High humidity in the surrounding air",B:"Closure of stomata at night",C:"High temperature combined with low humidity and air movement",D:"Darkness causing stomata to close"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Transpiration rate increases with: high temperature (more evaporation energy), low humidity (steeper water potential gradient between leaf and air), wind (removes humid air around leaf, maintaining gradient), and light (stomata open). High humidity and darkness both REDUCE transpiration." },
  { id:"bi5_34", question:"What is the function of auxin in phototropism?", options:{A:"Auxin causes cells on the light side to elongate faster",B:"Auxin migrates to the SHADED side, causing those cells to elongate more, bending the shoot toward light",C:"Auxin is produced only on the illuminated side of the shoot",D:"Auxin inhibits cell division on the shaded side"}, answer:"B", explanation:"In phototropism: unequal light causes lateral redistribution of auxin (IAA) to the shaded side. Higher auxin on the shaded side causes greater cell elongation there, bending the shoot toward the light. The mechanism is differential elongation, not differential division." },
  { id:"bi5_35", question:"Which type of immunity results from vaccination?", options:{A:"Natural passive immunity",B:"Natural active immunity",C:"Artificial passive immunity",D:"Artificial active immunity"}, answer:"D", explanation:"ARTIFICIAL ACTIVE immunity: achieved by introducing an antigen (vaccine) that stimulates the immune system to produce its own antibodies and memory cells, without causing full disease. Natural active = getting the disease. Passive = receiving ready-made antibodies (natural = across placenta; artificial = injection of antiserum)." },
  { id:"bi5_36", question:"Which blood cells are involved in the SPECIFIC immune response, producing antibodies?", options:{A:"Neutrophils",B:"Erythrocytes",C:"B lymphocytes (plasma cells)",D:"Platelets"}, answer:"C", explanation:"B lymphocytes, when activated by antigen presentation, differentiate into PLASMA CELLS which produce antibodies. T lymphocytes are also specific (cell-mediated immunity). Neutrophils are non-specific phagocytes. Erythrocytes carry O2; platelets are involved in clotting." },
  { id:"bi5_37", question:"In the Carbon cycle, which process returns CO2 to the atmosphere?", options:{A:"Photosynthesis",B:"Nitrogen fixation",C:"Respiration and combustion",D:"Transpiration"}, answer:"C", explanation:"RESPIRATION (all living organisms) and COMBUSTION (burning fossil fuels and biomass) return CO2 to the atmosphere. PHOTOSYNTHESIS removes CO2 from the atmosphere. Nitrogen fixation is part of the N cycle. Transpiration releases water vapour, not CO2." },
  { id:"bi5_38", question:"Which of the following is a correct definition of POPULATION DENSITY?", options:{A:"The total number of individuals of a species on Earth",B:"The number of different species in a given habitat",C:"The number of individuals of a species per unit area",D:"The rate of increase in population size per year"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Population density = number of individuals per unit area (or volume). It distinguishes crowded from sparse populations of the same size. Population size is total number. Species richness is the number of species. Rate of increase = (births + immigration) minus (deaths + emigration)." },
  { id:"bi5_39", question:"Xerophytes are plants adapted to survive in:", options:{A:"Waterlogged soils",B:"High-altitude environments",C:"Arid or water-scarce environments",D:"Shaded forest floors"}, answer:"C", explanation:"XEROPHYTES are adapted to dry (xero = dry) habitats. Adaptations include: thick waxy cuticle, sunken stomata, rolled leaves, CAM photosynthesis, deep or extensive root systems, water storage (succulents). HYDROPHYTES live in water; HALOPHYTES in salty conditions; MESOPHYTES in moderate conditions." },
  { id:"bi5_40", question:"What is the role of decomposers in an ecosystem?", options:{A:"They convert inorganic molecules into organic food for producers",B:"They break down dead organic matter, releasing nutrients back into the soil for producers to absorb",C:"They eat primary consumers and regulate prey populations",D:"They convert atmospheric nitrogen into ammonia"}, answer:"B", explanation:"DECOMPOSERS (fungi and bacteria): break down dead organic matter (detritus), releasing inorganic nutrients (nitrogen, phosphorus, carbon) back into the soil and atmosphere. Without decomposers, nutrients would remain locked in dead matter and producers could not grow. They close nutrient cycles." }
]; // end Biology[5]

DB["Chemistry"][5] = [
  { id:"ch5_1", question:"25.0 cm³ of 0.100 mol/dm³ NaOH is titrated against HCl. If 20.0 cm³ of HCl is required for neutralisation, what is the concentration of HCl?", options:{A:"0.125 mol/dm³",B:"0.100 mol/dm³",C:"0.080 mol/dm³",D:"0.250 mol/dm³"}, answer:"A", explanation:"NaOH + HCl -> NaCl + H2O (1:1 mole ratio). Moles NaOH = 0.025 × 0.100 = 0.0025 mol. Moles HCl = 0.0025 mol. Concentration HCl = 0.0025/0.020 = 0.125 mol/dm³. Always convert cm³ to dm³ (divide by 1000)." },
  { id:"ch5_2", question:"A 1.60 g sample of CuO is dissolved in excess dilute H2SO4 and the resulting solution is electrolysed. What mass of copper is deposited at the cathode? [Cu=64, O=16]", options:{A:"0.64 g",B:"1.28 g",C:"1.60 g",D:"3.20 g"}, answer:"B", explanation:"M(CuO)=80 g/mol. Moles CuO = 1.60/80 = 0.02 mol. CuO + H2SO4 -> CuSO4 + H2O, so moles Cu2+ = 0.02 mol. At cathode: Cu2+ + 2e- -> Cu. Moles Cu deposited = 0.02 mol. Mass = 0.02 × 64 = 1.28 g. The oxygen in CuO is lost to water." },
  { id:"ch5_3", question:"When a gas is compressed at constant temperature (Boyle's Law), which graph correctly represents the relationship?", options:{A:"P vs V is a straight line through the origin",B:"P vs 1/V is a straight line through the origin",C:"P vs V is an upward-sloping line",D:"P vs V² is a straight line"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Boyle's Law: PV = k (constant T). Rearranging: P = k(1/V). A graph of P vs 1/V is a straight line through the origin (y = kx). A graph of P vs V is a hyperbola (inverse relationship), NOT a straight line." },
  { id:"ch5_4", question:"Calculate the pH of a 0.01 mol/dm³ solution of HCl (a strong acid). [log 10 = 1]", options:{A:"pH = 1",B:"pH = 2",C:"pH = 12",D:"pH = 0"}, answer:"B", explanation:"HCl is a strong acid, fully dissociated. [H+] = 0.01 = 10⁻². pH = -log[H+] = -log(10⁻²) = 2. Note: pH = 1 would correspond to 0.1 mol/dm³; pH = 0 to 1.0 mol/dm³. Always check the power of 10." },
  { id:"ch5_5", question:"A weak acid HA has Ka = 1.0 × 10⁻⁵. What is the approximate [H+] in a 0.1 mol/dm³ solution?", options:{A:"1.0 × 10⁻³ mol/dm³",B:"1.0 × 10⁻⁵ mol/dm³",C:"1.0 × 10⁻⁶ mol/dm³",D:"1.0 × 10⁻² mol/dm³"}, answer:"A", explanation:"For a weak acid: [H+] = √(Ka × C) = √(1.0×10⁻⁵ × 0.1) = √(1.0×10⁻⁶) = 1.0×10⁻³ mol/dm³. This approximation (degree of dissociation << 1) is valid when Ka << C. pH = -log(10⁻³) = 3." },
  { id:"ch5_6", question:"Which of the following best explains why the boiling point of water (100°C) is much higher than that of H2S (-60°C), despite both being Group VI hydrides?", options:{A:"Water has a larger molar mass than H2S",B:"Water molecules form strong hydrogen bonds; H2S cannot form hydrogen bonds",C:"H2S molecules are larger and take more energy to separate",D:"Water has ionic bonds between H and O atoms"}, answer:"B", explanation:"O is highly electronegative (3.44) with lone pairs; H bonded to O carries a large partial positive charge. This creates strong O-H...O hydrogen bonds between water molecules. S is less electronegative (2.58), so H-S bonds are weakly polar and H2S cannot form effective hydrogen bonds. Only O, N, F form strong hydrogen bonds." },
  { id:"ch5_7", question:"In the contact process for sulphuric acid manufacture, why is SO3 absorbed in concentrated H2SO4 rather than water?", options:{A:"Water cannot react with SO3 under industrial conditions",B:"SO3 + H2O forms a dangerous acid mist rather than liquid H2SO4; concentrated H2SO4 gives liquid oleum safely",C:"Water would contaminate the sulphuric acid with NaCl",D:"Concentrated H2SO4 acts as a catalyst for SO3 absorption"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Direct absorption: SO3 + H2O -> H2SO4 produces a corrosive acid MIST (aerosol) that is difficult to handle and causes severe environmental and health problems. Industrially, SO3 is absorbed in 98% H2SO4 to form oleum (H2S2O7), which is then carefully diluted with water to give liquid H2SO4." },
  { id:"ch5_8", question:"What is the oxidation state of chromium in K2Cr2O7 (potassium dichromate)?", options:{A:"+3",B:"+4",C:"+6",D:"+7"}, answer:"C", explanation:"K2Cr2O7: K = +1, O = -2. Total: 2(+1) + 2(Cr) + 7(-2) = 0. 2 + 2Cr - 14 = 0. 2Cr = 12. Cr = +6. This is a standard JAMB redox question. Cr in +6 is the oxidised form (strong oxidising agent); Cr³+ is the reduced form." },
  { id:"ch5_9", question:"Which statement correctly distinguishes between STRONG and WEAK acids?", options:{A:"Strong acids have a higher molar mass than weak acids",B:"Strong acids are fully dissociated in aqueous solution; weak acids are only partially dissociated",C:"Strong acids are more concentrated than weak acids",D:"Weak acids are safer to handle than strong acids"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Strong acids (HCl, H2SO4, HNO3, HBr, HI, HClO4) dissociate completely: HCl -> H+ + Cl- (100%). Weak acids (CH3COOH, HCN, H2CO3) dissociate partially, establishing an equilibrium. Concentration and strength are independent. Concentrated ethanoic acid is still a WEAK acid." },
  { id:"ch5_10", question:"In the reaction between sodium thiosulphate and hydrochloric acid, the rate is measured by timing how long it takes for a cross to become invisible. What does this experiment measure?", options:{A:"pH change during the reaction",B:"Rate of gas evolution",C:"Rate of precipitate formation (sulphur) making the solution opaque",D:"Colour change due to an indicator"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Na2S2O3 + 2HCl -> 2NaCl + SO2 + S + H2O. Colloidal sulphur forms as a precipitate, making the solution progressively cloudy. The cross drawn under the flask becomes invisible when enough sulphur has formed. This is a classic clock reaction used to study the effect of concentration and temperature on rate." },
  { id:"ch5_11", question:"Using Le Chatelier's principle, what happens to the equilibrium position of N2 + 3H2 = 2NH3 if the pressure is INCREASED?", options:{A:"Equilibrium shifts left (toward reactants)",B:"Equilibrium shifts right (toward products)",C:"Equilibrium is unaffected by pressure changes",D:"Temperature increases cause the same effect as pressure increases"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Increasing pressure favours the side with FEWER moles of gas. Left side: 1+3 = 4 moles of gas. Right side: 2 moles of gas. Equilibrium shifts RIGHT (toward fewer moles), producing more NH3. This is why the Haber process uses high pressure (~200 atm)." },
  { id:"ch5_12", question:"Which of the following is the correct test for a REDUCING sugar?", options:{A:"Add iodine solution; blue-black colour confirms reducing sugar",B:"Add Fehling's solution and heat; brick-red precipitate confirms reducing sugar",C:"Add silver nitrate solution; white precipitate confirms reducing sugar",D:"Add Benedict's reagent cold; immediate colour change confirms reducing sugar"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Fehling's (and Benedict's) solution contains Cu²+ in alkaline solution. A REDUCING sugar donates electrons (reduces Cu²+ to Cu+), forming a brick-red Cu2O precipitate on heating. Iodine tests for starch. Silver nitrate tests for halides. Benedict's reagent requires heating, not cold application." },
  { id:"ch5_13", question:"Which functional group is present in a CARBOXYLIC ACID?", options:{A:"-OH",B:"-CHO",C:"-COOH",D:"-CO-"}, answer:"C", explanation:"-COOH (carboxyl group) = a carbonyl group (C=O) AND a hydroxyl group (-OH) on the SAME carbon. Carboxylic acids are weak acids due to the ionisable O-H proton. -OH alone is an alcohol. -CHO is an aldehyde. -CO- (with two carbons attached) is a ketone." },
  { id:"ch5_14", question:"Esterification is the reaction between:", options:{A:"An alcohol and a carboxylic acid, producing an ester and water",B:"An alkene and water, producing an alcohol",C:"Two carboxylic acids, producing an anhydride",D:"An amine and an acid chloride, producing an amide"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Esterification: RCOOH + R'OH = RCOOR' + H2O. Requires concentrated H2SO4 catalyst, heat, and is reversible. Esters have the functional group -COO-. They have fruity smells and are used in perfumes, flavourings, and solvents. The reaction is hydrolysis in reverse." },
  { id:"ch5_15", question:"Saponification is the alkaline hydrolysis of:", options:{A:"Proteins to amino acids",B:"Esters (specifically fats/oils) to soap (fatty acid salts) and glycerol",C:"Starch to glucose",D:"Amides to carboxylic acids"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Saponification: fat (triester of glycerol with three fatty acids) + NaOH -> sodium salt of fatty acid (soap) + glycerol. The word saponification comes from Latin sapo (soap). Industrial soap-making uses this reaction. The sodium salts of long-chain fatty acids are soaps." },
  { id:"ch5_16", question:"What is the IUPAC name of CH3CH2CH2CH2OH?", options:{A:"Butanal",B:"Butan-2-ol",C:"Butan-1-ol",D:"2-methylpropan-1-ol"}, answer:"C", explanation:"CH3CH2CH2CH2OH: 4-carbon chain = butane; OH group at C1 = ol at position 1; no other substituents. IUPAC name: butan-1-ol. Butanal would be CH3CH2CH2CHO (an aldehyde). Butan-2-ol has OH on C2. 2-methylpropan-1-ol is (CH3)2CHCH2OH." },
  { id:"ch5_17", question:"Which statement about alkenes is CORRECT?", options:{A:"Alkenes are saturated hydrocarbons that undergo substitution reactions",B:"Alkenes contain at least one C=C double bond and undergo addition reactions",C:"Alkenes are aromatic compounds with delocalised pi electrons",D:"Alkenes cannot react with bromine water"}, answer:"B", explanation:"ALKENES: unsaturated (C=C double bond), general formula CnH2n, undergo ELECTROPHILIC ADDITION reactions. Saturated hydrocarbons are ALKANES (undergo substitution). Aromatic compounds are benzene ring systems. Alkenes decolourise bromine water via addition (Br2 adds across C=C)." },
  { id:"ch5_18", question:"In what type of chemical bond do two atoms share TWO pairs of electrons?", options:{A:"Single covalent bond",B:"Ionic bond",C:"Double covalent bond",D:"Dative (coordinate) bond"}, answer:"C", explanation:"A DOUBLE covalent bond involves sharing 2 pairs (4 electrons total) between two atoms. Example: C=C in ethene, C=O in CO2. Single bond = 1 pair shared. Triple bond = 3 pairs shared. Ionic bond = electron transfer. Dative bond = both electrons from one atom." },
  { id:"ch5_19", question:"Which of the following is a property of IONIC compounds?", options:{A:"They have low melting points and are good conductors of electricity as solids",B:"They are volatile liquids at room temperature",C:"They have high melting points and conduct electricity when molten or dissolved in water",D:"They are soluble only in non-polar solvents like benzene"}, answer:"C", explanation:"IONIC compounds: strong electrostatic lattice forces require large energy to overcome (high melting and boiling points). As solids, ions are fixed (no conduction). When melted or dissolved, ions are mobile and can carry charge (electrolytic conduction). They dissolve in polar solvents (water), not non-polar ones." },
  { id:"ch5_20", question:"What type of reaction converts an alkane to an alkene under high temperature without oxygen?", options:{A:"Combustion",B:"Cracking (thermal or catalytic)",C:"Halogenation",D:"Polymerisation"}, answer:"B", explanation:"CRACKING: long-chain alkanes are broken into shorter alkanes and alkenes by high temperature (thermal cracking) or moderate temperature with catalyst (catalytic cracking). Industrially used to convert heavy oil fractions into petrol (shorter alkanes) and alkenes for chemical feedstocks." },
  { id:"ch5_21", question:"What is the approximate percentage composition by mass of carbon in ethanol (C2H5OH)? [C=12, H=1, O=16]", options:{A:"26.1%",B:"34.8%",C:"52.2%",D:"13.0%"}, answer:"C", explanation:"M(C2H5OH) = 2(12)+6(1)+16 = 24+6+16 = 46 g/mol. Mass of C = 2×12 = 24. %C = 24/46 × 100 = 52.17% ≈ 52.2%. Standard percentage composition question: always calculate molar mass first, then divide mass of element by total." },
  { id:"ch5_22", question:"Which product forms when calcium carbonate is strongly heated (thermal decomposition)?", options:{A:"CaO + CO2",B:"Ca + CO2 + O2",C:"Ca(OH)2 + CO",D:"CaCO3 remains unchanged"}, answer:"A", explanation:"CaCO3 -> CaO + CO2 (at 840-900°C). This is thermal decomposition. CaO (quicklime) is used in cement and steel. CO2 is released. Adding water to CaO gives Ca(OH)2 (slaked lime). This reaction is the basis of the lime kiln." },
  { id:"ch5_23", question:"In the reactivity series, if zinc is placed in copper sulphate solution, which observation would you expect?", options:{A:"No reaction; zinc is less reactive than copper",B:"Zinc dissolves; copper metal deposits on the zinc surface",C:"Blue solution turns colourless and zinc grows larger",D:"A blue precipitate forms in the solution"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Zn is MORE reactive (higher in the reactivity series) than Cu. Displacement reaction: Zn + CuSO4 -> ZnSO4 + Cu. Zinc DISSOLVES (Zn -> Zn2+ + 2e-); copper metal DEPOSITS (Cu2+ + 2e- -> Cu). Solution turns from blue (Cu2+) to colourless (Zn2+). Zinc appears to corrode while copper coats the surface." },
  { id:"ch5_24", question:"Which test would confirm the presence of the ammonium ion (NH4+) in a solution?", options:{A:"Add dilute HCl; effervescence confirms NH4+",B:"Add NaOH and warm; pungent gas that turns moist red litmus blue is NH3",C:"Add silver nitrate; white precipitate confirms NH4+",D:"Add BaCl2; white precipitate confirms NH4+"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Test for NH4+: add NaOH (or warm NaOH) to the solution; NH4+ is converted to NH3. 2NH4+ + 2OH- -> 2NH3 + 2H2O. Ammonia is identified by: (1) pungent smell; (2) turns moist red litmus blue (NH3 is alkaline). BaCl2 tests for SO4²-. AgNO3 tests for halides. HCl tests for carbonates (CO2)." },
  { id:"ch5_25", question:"What is the observation when chlorine gas is bubbled through a solution of potassium iodide?", options:{A:"No reaction; chlorine is less reactive than iodine",B:"The solution turns blue when starch paper is applied; iodine is displaced by chlorine",C:"A white precipitate forms",D:"The solution turns bright red permanently"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Cl2 is more reactive than I2. Displacement: Cl2 + 2KI -> 2KCl + I2. Iodine is liberated; the solution turns brown/orange (I2 in water). On starch paper, I2 gives a BLUE-BLACK colour. This confirms halide displacement, a key halogen reactivity test." },
  { id:"ch5_26", question:"Which of the following is the correct electron configuration of the chloride ion (Cl⁻)? [Z(Cl)=17]", options:{A:"2,8,7",B:"2,8,8",C:"2,8,9",D:"2,8,6"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Neutral Cl: Z=17; configuration = 2,8,7. Cl⁻ gains ONE electron: configuration = 2,8,8 (same as argon). The extra electron fills the 3p subshell. Anions gain electrons; cations lose electrons. Cl⁻ has a stable noble gas configuration." },
  { id:"ch5_27", question:"Which of the following represents an EXOTHERMIC reaction?", options:{A:"Thermal decomposition of CaCO3",B:"Photosynthesis",C:"Combustion of propane",D:"Dissolving ammonium nitrate in water"}, answer:"C", explanation:"EXOTHERMIC reactions release heat (DH < 0, negative). Combustion of propane: C3H8 + 5O2 -> 3CO2 + 4H2O; DH = -2219 kJ/mol. Thermal decomposition and photosynthesis are ENDOTHERMIC (absorb heat). NH4NO3 dissolving absorbs heat (feels cold), so it too is endothermic." },
  { id:"ch5_28", question:"What does the term 'molar enthalpy of neutralisation' refer to?", options:{A:"The enthalpy change when one mole of acid is made",B:"The enthalpy change when one mole of water is formed in an acid-base reaction under standard conditions",C:"The total heat produced in a neutralisation reaction",D:"The enthalpy change when one mole of base is dissolved in water"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Standard molar enthalpy of neutralisation: the heat released when an acid and a base react to form ONE MOLE of water under standard conditions. For strong acid + strong base: approximately -57 kJ/mol (always exothermic). Weak acid or base values are less exothermic due to enthalpy of dissociation." },
  { id:"ch5_29", question:"Which homologous series has the general formula CnH(2n+2)?", options:{A:"Alkenes",B:"Alkynes",C:"Alkanes",D:"Cycloalkanes"}, answer:"C", explanation:"ALKANES: CnH(2n+2); saturated; e.g., methane CH4 (n=1), ethane C2H6 (n=2), propane C3H8 (n=3). ALKENES: CnH2n (one double bond). ALKYNES: CnH(2n-2) (one triple bond). CYCLOALKANES: CnH2n (ring, no double bond, same general formula as alkenes)." },
  { id:"ch5_30", question:"What is the approximate bond angle in a tetrahedral molecule such as methane (CH4)?", options:{A:"90°",B:"109.5°",C:"120°",D:"180°"}, answer:"B", explanation:"TETRAHEDRAL: 4 bonding pairs, 0 lone pairs. VSEPR theory: four electron pairs arrange themselves at 109.5° to minimise repulsion. CH4, SiH4, CCl4 are tetrahedral with 109.5° bond angles. NH3 (pyramidal with 1 lone pair) = 107°. H2O (bent with 2 lone pairs) = 104.5°." },
  { id:"ch5_31", question:"Which of these is the CORRECT product of the reaction between ethanol and acidified potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7)?", options:{A:"Ethene only",B:"Ethanoic acid (if oxidation is complete) or ethanal (partial)",C:"Ethyl ethanoate",D:"Methanol"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Oxidation of ethanol with acidified K2Cr2O7 (Cr changes from +6 to +3, orange to green): Partial (reflux): CH3CH2OH -> CH3CHO (ethanal, aldehyde). Full (excess oxidant, distil over): CH3CH2OH -> CH3COOH (ethanoic acid). The Cr changes from orange dichromate to green Cr³+." },
  { id:"ch5_32", question:"A molecule of glucose (C6H12O6) is classified as:", options:{A:"A disaccharide",B:"A lipid",C:"A monosaccharide (hexose sugar)",D:"A polysaccharide"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Glucose (C6H12O6) is a MONOSACCHARIDE (single sugar unit). Hexose = 6 carbons. Disaccharides: two monosaccharides joined (e.g., sucrose = glucose + fructose). Polysaccharides: many monosaccharide units (e.g., starch, glycogen, cellulose). Lipids have a glycerol backbone with fatty acids." },
  { id:"ch5_33", question:"What type of bond links amino acids together in a protein chain?", options:{A:"Glycosidic bond",B:"Ester bond",C:"Peptide bond (amide bond)",D:"Hydrogen bond"}, answer:"C", explanation:"PEPTIDE BOND: formed by condensation reaction between the amino group (-NH2) of one amino acid and the carboxyl group (-COOH) of another, with loss of water. -CO-NH- linkage = peptide (amide) bond. Glycosidic bonds link sugars. Ester bonds link glycerol to fatty acids. Hydrogen bonds maintain protein secondary structure." },
  { id:"ch5_34", question:"In the preparation of a standard solution, what is the first step?", options:{A:"Weigh the solute approximately on any balance",B:"Accurately weigh a primary standard substance and dissolve it in the exact volume of solvent in a volumetric flask",C:"Mix the solute with any available volume of water",D:"Use any acid-base indicator to check the concentration"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Standard solution preparation: (1) accurately weigh a primary standard (pure, stable, high molar mass substance: e.g., Na2CO3, anhydrous Na2CO3, KIO3); (2) dissolve in distilled water; (3) quantitatively transfer to a volumetric flask; (4) make up to the mark. Accuracy of weighing and volumetric flask are critical." },
  { id:"ch5_35", question:"When excess dilute HNO3 is added to copper, the main gas produced is:", options:{A:"NO2 (brown gas)",B:"NO (colourless gas that turns brown in air)",C:"N2O",D:"H2"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Dilute HNO3 + Cu: 3Cu + 8HNO3(dilute) -> 3Cu(NO3)2 + 2NO + 4H2O. NO (colourless) is produced with dilute acid. NO rapidly oxidises in air to brown NO2. Concentrated HNO3 produces NO2 directly. Copper does NOT produce H2 (copper is below hydrogen in the reactivity series, so cannot displace H2)." },
  { id:"ch5_36", question:"Which of the following statements about the periodic table is CORRECT?", options:{A:"Atomic radius increases across a period from left to right",B:"Electronegativity decreases down a group",C:"Ionisation energy generally increases across a period from left to right",D:"Metallic character increases across a period from left to right"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Across a period (L to R): nuclear charge increases, atomic radius decreases, ionisation energy generally increases (more energy needed to remove electron from smaller, more positive atom), electronegativity increases, metallic character decreases. Down a group: IE decreases, radius increases, metallic character increases." },
  { id:"ch5_37", question:"The process of zone refining is used to:", options:{A:"Remove sulphur from iron during steel production",B:"Purify metals (e.g., silicon for semiconductors) to extremely high purity",C:"Convert iron ore to pig iron in a blast furnace",D:"Electroplate metals with a thin coating of another metal"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Zone refining: a narrow molten zone is passed slowly along a rod of the impure metal. Impurities are more soluble in the melt than in the solid and concentrate in the molten zone, which is swept to one end. Used to produce ultra-pure metals and semiconductors (silicon, germanium). Distinct from other purification methods." },
  { id:"ch5_38", question:"When iron rusts, it forms hydrated iron(III) oxide. What two substances are essential for rusting?", options:{A:"Carbon dioxide and nitrogen",B:"Water and oxygen",C:"Salt and carbon dioxide",D:"Hydrogen and nitrogen"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Rusting of iron requires BOTH water AND oxygen simultaneously. The electrochemical mechanism involves iron (anode) oxidising to Fe²+ and oxygen (cathode) being reduced. Salt (NaCl) in seawater ACCELERATES rusting by increasing electrolyte conductivity, but is not essential." },
  { id:"ch5_39", question:"Which of the following correctly describes the difference between a SATURATED and UNSATURATED solution?", options:{A:"Saturated solutions contain only ionic compounds; unsaturated contain covalent compounds",B:"A saturated solution contains the maximum amount of dissolved solute at a given temperature; an unsaturated solution could dissolve more",C:"Unsaturated solutions are more concentrated than saturated ones",D:"Saturated solutions are always clear; unsaturated solutions are always coloured"}, answer:"B", explanation:"SATURATED solution: at equilibrium - solute is dissolving and recrystallising at equal rates; cannot dissolve more at that temperature. UNSATURATED: less solute than saturation concentration - more can be dissolved. SUPERSATURATED: more dissolved than usual saturation (unstable). These are physical states, not related to ionic vs. covalent." },
  { id:"ch5_40", question:"What is the function of a catalyst in a chemical reaction?", options:{A:"It increases the activation energy of both forward and reverse reactions",B:"It shifts the equilibrium position to favour the products",C:"It provides an alternative reaction pathway with a lower activation energy, increasing reaction rate without being consumed",D:"It increases the temperature of the reaction mixture"}, answer:"C", explanation:"A catalyst provides an ALTERNATIVE PATHWAY with LOWER activation energy. More reactant molecules have sufficient energy to react, increasing rate. Crucially: (1) it is NOT consumed; (2) it does NOT change DH or equilibrium position; (3) it speeds up BOTH forward and reverse reactions equally." }
]; // end Chemistry[5]

DB["Physics"][5] = [
  { id:"ph5_1", question:"A car accelerates uniformly from rest to 30 m/s in 10 s. What is the distance covered?", options:{A:"300 m",B:"150 m",C:"60 m",D:"450 m"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Using s = ut + ½at². u=0 (from rest), t=10 s. First find a: v=u+at → 30=0+10a → a=3 m/s². s = 0 + ½(3)(100) = 150 m. Alternatively: s = (u+v)/2 × t = (0+30)/2 × 10 = 15 × 10 = 150 m. Always use the average velocity shortcut when acceleration is uniform." },
  { id:"ph5_2", question:"A 2 kg mass is thrown vertically upward with an initial velocity of 20 m/s. What maximum height does it reach? [g = 10 m/s²]", options:{A:"40 m",B:"20 m",C:"10 m",D:"200 m"}, answer:"B", explanation:"At maximum height, v=0. Using v²=u²-2gs: 0 = 400 - 2(10)s → 20s = 400 → s = 20 m. Alternatively: time to top = v/g = 20/10 = 2 s; s = ut - ½gt² = 20(2) - ½(10)(4) = 40-20 = 20 m. The mass (2 kg) is irrelevant as g applies equally to all masses." },
  { id:"ph5_3", question:"A body of mass 5 kg moving at 4 m/s collides with a stationary 3 kg body. They stick together (perfectly inelastic collision). What is their common velocity after collision?", options:{A:"4 m/s",B:"2.5 m/s",C:"1.5 m/s",D:"5.0 m/s"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Conservation of momentum: m1u1 + m2u2 = (m1+m2)v. 5(4) + 3(0) = (5+3)v. 20 = 8v. v = 2.5 m/s. In a perfectly inelastic collision, objects stick together. Kinetic energy is NOT conserved (only momentum). Note: kinetic energy loss = ½(5)(16) - ½(8)(6.25) = 40 - 25 = 15 J." },
  { id:"ph5_4", question:"A car of mass 1000 kg travelling at 20 m/s brakes to a stop. What is the impulse on the car?", options:{A:"20,000 N·s away from original direction",B:"20,000 N·s in original direction",C:"1000 N·s",D:"200 N·s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Impulse = change in momentum = m(v-u) = 1000(0-20) = -20,000 kg·m/s. Magnitude = 20,000 N·s, directed OPPOSITE to original motion (the braking force acts backwards). Impulse equals force × time and equals the change in momentum." },
  { id:"ph5_5", question:"What is the gravitational potential energy of a 4 kg object at a height of 5 m above the ground? [g = 10 m/s²]", options:{A:"200 J",B:"20 J",C:"2000 J",D:"50 J"}, answer:"A", explanation:"GPE = mgh = 4 × 10 × 5 = 200 J. This energy is stored as potential energy and would be converted to kinetic energy if the object fell. At the bottom, all GPE converts to KE (ignoring air resistance): ½mv² = 200 → v² = 100 → v = 10 m/s." },
  { id:"ph5_6", question:"In a simple machine, the mechanical advantage (MA) is defined as:", options:{A:"Work output divided by work input",B:"Load divided by effort",C:"Distance moved by effort divided by distance moved by load",D:"Velocity ratio multiplied by efficiency"}, answer:"B", explanation:"MA = Load / Effort. It tells how many times the machine multiplies the applied force. VR (Velocity Ratio) = distance moved by effort / distance moved by load. Efficiency = (MA/VR) × 100%. Note: MA = VR × efficiency (when expressed as a fraction). In an ideal machine, MA = VR." },
  { id:"ph5_7", question:"The specific heat capacity of water is 4200 J/(kg·K). How much energy is needed to heat 2 kg of water from 25°C to 75°C?", options:{A:"420,000 J",B:"210,000 J",C:"630,000 J",D:"84,000 J"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Q = mcΔT = 2 × 4200 × (75-25) = 2 × 4200 × 50 = 420,000 J = 420 kJ. ΔT = 50 K (same as 50°C change). The specific heat capacity defines the energy per kilogram per kelvin. Always check the temperature difference, not the absolute temperatures." },
  { id:"ph5_8", question:"Heat is transferred through a vacuum primarily by:", options:{A:"Conduction",B:"Convection",C:"Radiation",D:"All three equally"}, answer:"C", explanation:"RADIATION (electromagnetic waves, primarily infrared) requires NO medium and can travel through a vacuum. CONDUCTION requires physical contact between particles. CONVECTION requires a fluid (liquid or gas) to carry heat by bulk movement. This is why the sun's energy reaches Earth through the vacuum of space." },
  { id:"ph5_9", question:"A gas at 27°C is heated at constant pressure until its volume doubles. What is the new temperature?", options:{A:"54°C",B:"327°C",C:"300°C",D:"600°C"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Charles's Law (constant P): V1/T1 = V2/T2. T must be in KELVIN. T1 = 27+273 = 300 K. V2 = 2V1. 300/V1 = T2/(2V1) → T2 = 600 K = 600-273 = 327°C. Common error: forgetting to convert to Kelvin. If you used 27×2=54°C, that is wrong because 0°C ≠ 0 K." },
  { id:"ph5_10", question:"Which wave property determines the PITCH of a sound?", options:{A:"Amplitude",B:"Frequency",C:"Speed",D:"Wavelength alone"}, answer:"B", explanation:"FREQUENCY determines PITCH. Higher frequency = higher pitch. AMPLITUDE determines LOUDNESS (or intensity). The speed of sound in a given medium is constant (343 m/s in air at 20°C) and does not determine pitch. Wavelength and frequency are related by v = fλ, so for constant speed, higher frequency means shorter wavelength." },
  { id:"ph5_11", question:"A sound wave has a frequency of 440 Hz and a wavelength of 0.78 m. What is the speed of sound?", options:{A:"343 m/s",B:"565 m/s",C:"440 m/s",D:"220 m/s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"v = fλ = 440 × 0.78 = 343.2 ≈ 343 m/s. This is the standard speed of sound in air at room temperature. The question confirms v = fλ is the wave equation. Always check: frequency in Hz, wavelength in m, speed in m/s." },
  { id:"ph5_12", question:"A light ray travelling in glass (n=1.5) hits the glass-air boundary at 45°. What is the angle of refraction in air? [sin 45° ≈ 0.707]", options:{A:"28.1°",B:"45°",C:"90°",D:"The ray undergoes total internal reflection"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Critical angle for glass-air: sin(c) = n_air/n_glass = 1/1.5 = 0.667 → c ≈ 41.8°. Since the incident angle (45°) exceeds the critical angle (41.8°), TOTAL INTERNAL REFLECTION occurs. No light is transmitted into the air; all light reflects back into the glass. This is the principle behind optical fibres." },
  { id:"ph5_13", question:"Two resistors of 6Ω and 3Ω are connected in PARALLEL across a 12V battery. What is the total current from the battery?", options:{A:"1 A",B:"2 A",C:"6 A",D:"4 A"}, answer:"C", explanation:"For parallel resistors: 1/R = 1/6 + 1/3 = 1/6 + 2/6 = 3/6 = 1/2 → R = 2Ω. Total current: I = V/R = 12/2 = 6 A. Alternatively: I₁ = 12/6 = 2 A; I₂ = 12/3 = 4 A; total = 6 A. In parallel, voltage across each resistor is the same (12V) but currents add." },
  { id:"ph5_14", question:"A charge of 120 C passes through a wire in 4 minutes. What is the current?", options:{A:"30 A",B:"0.5 A",C:"480 A",D:"8 A"}, answer:"B", explanation:"I = Q/t. t = 4 min = 4 × 60 = 240 s. I = 120/240 = 0.5 A. Always convert time to SECONDS when using I = Q/t. Current in amperes = coulombs per second." },
  { id:"ph5_15", question:"Which of the following correctly describes the PHOTOELECTRIC EFFECT?", options:{A:"Electrons are emitted from a metal surface when electromagnetic radiation above a threshold frequency is incident on it",B:"A metal emits photons when electrons pass through it",C:"Light is bent as it passes close to a massive body",D:"Electrons orbit the nucleus in discrete energy levels"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Photoelectric effect (Einstein, 1905): when light of frequency above a minimum threshold (f > f₀) hits a metal surface, electrons are emitted. Below threshold, no emission occurs regardless of intensity. One photon ejects one electron. Kinetic energy of electron = hf - work function (φ). This proved light behaves as particles (photons)." },
  { id:"ph5_16", question:"What is the de Broglie wavelength of an electron of momentum p?", options:{A:"λ = hp",B:"λ = p/h",C:"λ = h/p",D:"λ = p/m"}, answer:"C", explanation:"de Broglie hypothesis (1924): all matter has wave properties. λ = h/p = h/(mv). Planck's constant h = 6.63×10⁻³⁴ J·s. This explains why electrons can be diffracted (wave behaviour) and why atomic electrons occupy discrete energy levels (standing wave condition). Wave-particle duality applies to all matter." },
  { id:"ph5_17", question:"In a step-down transformer, if the primary has 2000 turns and the secondary has 200 turns, and the primary voltage is 440V, what is the secondary voltage?", options:{A:"4400 V",B:"44 V",C:"440 V",D:"22 V"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Vs/Vp = Ns/Np. Vs = Vp × (Ns/Np) = 440 × (200/2000) = 440 × 0.1 = 44 V. Step-DOWN: fewer secondary turns than primary. Step-UP: more secondary turns. Assuming 100% efficiency: IpVp = IsVs (power conserved)." },
  { id:"ph5_18", question:"What is the half-life of a radioactive substance if 80 g decays to 10 g in 18 days?", options:{A:"3 days",B:"6 days",C:"9 days",D:"18 days"}, answer:"B", explanation:"80 → 40 (1 half-life) → 20 (2 half-lives) → 10 (3 half-lives). So 3 half-lives = 18 days → half-life = 18/3 = 6 days. The mass halves with each half-life. Count the number of halvings needed: 80/10 = 8 = 2³, so 3 half-lives are needed." },
  { id:"ph5_19", question:"In nuclear fission of U-235, if 1 neutron is absorbed and 3 neutrons are produced, what phenomenon does this enable?", options:{A:"Fusion",B:"Radioactive decay",C:"A chain reaction",D:"Beta emission"}, answer:"C", explanation:"If each fission event produces more neutrons than it consumes (here: 3 out > 1 in), those neutrons can trigger further fissions. This self-sustaining CHAIN REACTION can be controlled (nuclear reactor) or uncontrolled (nuclear bomb). Critical mass is required for sustained fission." },
  { id:"ph5_20", question:"An object is placed 30 cm in front of a converging lens of focal length 10 cm. Using the thin lens formula, find the image distance.", options:{A:"7.5 cm",B:"15 cm",C:"20 cm",D:"30 cm"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Thin lens formula: 1/v - 1/u = 1/f. Using sign convention (real is positive): 1/v = 1/f + 1/u = 1/10 + 1/(-30)? Using 1/v = 1/f - 1/|u| for real object: 1/v = 1/10 - 1/30 = 3/30 - 1/30 = 2/30 → v = 15 cm. The image is real and on the opposite side of the lens from the object." },
  { id:"ph5_21", question:"Which of the following is a VECTOR quantity?", options:{A:"Speed",B:"Mass",C:"Temperature",D:"Displacement"}, answer:"D", explanation:"VECTOR quantities have both magnitude and direction: displacement, velocity, acceleration, force, momentum, weight. SCALAR quantities have magnitude only: speed, mass, temperature, distance, time, energy. Displacement = straight-line distance in a specified direction; speed = distance/time (no direction)." },
  { id:"ph5_22", question:"A 60 W lamp is used for 5 hours. How much electrical energy is consumed in kWh?", options:{A:"0.3 kWh",B:"300 kWh",C:"12 kWh",D:"0.12 kWh"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Energy = Power × time = 60 W × 5 h = 300 Wh = 0.3 kWh. Convert W to kW: 60/1000 = 0.06 kW. Energy = 0.06 × 5 = 0.3 kWh. Electricity bills use kWh (1 unit = 1 kWh). In joules: 300 Wh × 3600 = 1,080,000 J = 1.08 MJ." },
  { id:"ph5_23", question:"What does Archimedes' principle state?", options:{A:"An object in a fluid sinks if its density is greater than the fluid",B:"A body immersed in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced",C:"The pressure in a fluid increases linearly with volume",D:"A floating object displaces its own volume of fluid"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Archimedes' principle: buoyant force = weight of fluid displaced. This applies whether the object floats or sinks. A floating object (equilibrium) displaces fluid whose weight equals the object's weight (not volume). A sinking object displaces its own VOLUME; a floating object displaces less than its volume." },
  { id:"ph5_24", question:"Which of the following best explains why a wire carrying current in a magnetic field experiences a force?", options:{A:"The magnetic field induces an EMF in the wire",B:"Moving charges (electrons) in the wire experience a force (F=BIL sinθ) from the external magnetic field",C:"The wire becomes magnetised and is attracted to the magnet",D:"Heat generated in the wire creates a pressure force"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The force on a current-carrying conductor: F = BIL sinθ where B=magnetic field, I=current, L=length. This arises because the moving charges (electrons constituting current) experience a magnetic force F = qv × B. This is the motor effect, the principle behind electric motors." },
  { id:"ph5_25", question:"By Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction, an EMF is induced in a conductor when:", options:{A:"The conductor is stationary in a constant magnetic field",B:"The magnetic flux linking the conductor is CHANGING",C:"A high current passes through the conductor",D:"The conductor is heated above its Curie temperature"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Faraday's law: induced EMF = -dΦ/dt (rate of change of magnetic flux). An EMF is induced ONLY when flux is CHANGING (by moving the magnet, moving the conductor, or changing the current in an adjacent coil). A conductor at rest in a CONSTANT field has no changing flux and no induced EMF." },
  { id:"ph5_26", question:"What is the relationship between the pressure at depth h in a fluid of density ρ?", options:{A:"P = ρg/h",B:"P = ρgh",C:"P = gh/ρ",D:"P = ρ/gh"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Pressure at depth: P = ρgh. Where ρ = fluid density (kg/m³), g = 9.8 m/s², h = depth below surface (m). P is in pascals (Pa = N/m²). This is fluid (hydrostatic) pressure, additional to atmospheric pressure. Example: 10 m depth in water: P = 1000 × 10 × 10 = 100,000 Pa = 1 atm extra." },
  { id:"ph5_27", question:"A thermometer reads 37°C. What is the equivalent in Kelvin?", options:{A:"310 K",B:"236 K",C:"100 K",D:"373 K"}, answer:"A", explanation:"K = °C + 273. 37 + 273 = 310 K. The Kelvin scale starts at absolute zero (-273°C), the point of minimum thermal energy. Water freezes at 273 K; boils at 373 K. NEVER use Celsius in gas law calculations; always convert to Kelvin first." },
  { id:"ph5_28", question:"In Young's double-slit experiment, if the slit separation is doubled while everything else remains constant, what happens to the fringe separation?", options:{A:"Fringe separation doubles",B:"Fringe separation quadruples",C:"Fringe separation halves",D:"Fringe separation is unchanged"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Fringe separation: Δy = λD/d. Where λ=wavelength, D=slit-to-screen distance, d=slit separation. Doubling d (slit separation) while keeping λ and D constant: Δy = λD/(2d) = half the original fringe separation. Fringes become closer together." },
  { id:"ph5_29", question:"Which type of electromagnetic radiation has the HIGHEST frequency?", options:{A:"Radio waves",B:"Visible light",C:"X-rays",D:"Gamma rays"}, answer:"D", explanation:"EM spectrum in order of increasing frequency (decreasing wavelength): Radio < Microwaves < Infrared < Visible < Ultraviolet < X-rays < Gamma rays. Gamma rays have the highest frequency and shortest wavelength, and the most penetrating power and energy per photon (E = hf)." },
  { id:"ph5_30", question:"A resistor of 4Ω carries a current of 3A for 10 seconds. How much heat is generated?", options:{A:"120 J",B:"360 J",C:"180 J",D:"40 J"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Heat generated: Q = I²Rt = (3)²(4)(10) = 9 × 4 × 10 = 360 J. This is Joule's heating law. Alternatively: P = I²R = 9×4 = 36 W; Q = Pt = 36×10 = 360 J. The heat is proportional to I², so doubling current quadruples heat." },
  { id:"ph5_31", question:"The principle of conservation of energy states that:", options:{A:"Energy can be created in chemical reactions but not destroyed",B:"Total energy of an isolated system remains constant; energy can only be transformed from one form to another",C:"Potential energy always equals kinetic energy",D:"The total energy of all systems in the universe is zero"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Conservation of energy (First Law of Thermodynamics): energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed. In mechanics: total mechanical energy (KE + PE) is conserved when only conservative forces act. In real situations, some energy is always transformed to heat (not lost, just less useful)." },
  { id:"ph5_32", question:"Which statement correctly describes the motion of a projectile (ignoring air resistance)?", options:{A:"Both horizontal and vertical components of velocity are constant",B:"The horizontal velocity is constant; the vertical velocity changes due to gravity",C:"Both components change due to gravity acting in all directions",D:"The vertical velocity is constant; horizontal velocity changes due to drag"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Projectile motion: HORIZONTAL velocity is constant (no horizontal force acts, ignoring air resistance). VERTICAL velocity changes at rate g = 9.8 m/s² (gravity acts downward). The path is parabolic. These two motions are INDEPENDENT and can be analysed separately." },
  { id:"ph5_33", question:"What does Ohm's law state?", options:{A:"Current is directly proportional to resistance at constant voltage",B:"Voltage across a conductor is directly proportional to the current through it, provided temperature and other physical conditions remain constant",C:"Resistance increases as current increases in all conductors",D:"Power equals current squared divided by resistance"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Ohm's law: V = IR (voltage proportional to current at constant temperature). A conductor that obeys Ohm's law (straight line through origin on V-I graph) is 'ohmic'. Non-ohmic components (diodes, bulbs, thermistors) do NOT have constant resistance. Ohm's law requires constant temperature." },
  { id:"ph5_34", question:"A simple pendulum has a period of 2 s. What is its length? [g = 10 m/s², π² ≈ 10]", options:{A:"0.5 m",B:"1.0 m",C:"2.0 m",D:"4.0 m"}, answer:"B", explanation:"T = 2π√(L/g). Squaring: T² = 4π²L/g. L = gT²/(4π²) = 10×4/(4×10) = 40/40 = 1.0 m. Note: π² ≈ 9.87 ≈ 10 is given. The pendulum's period depends only on length and g, NOT on amplitude (for small angles) or mass." },
  { id:"ph5_35", question:"What is the difference between nuclear FISSION and nuclear FUSION?", options:{A:"Fission involves light nuclei joining; fusion involves heavy nuclei splitting",B:"Fission splits heavy nuclei into lighter ones releasing energy; fusion joins light nuclei to form heavier ones releasing energy",C:"Only fission releases energy; fusion absorbs energy",D:"Fission occurs in stars; fusion occurs in nuclear power plants"}, answer:"B", explanation:"FISSION: heavy nucleus (U-235) splits into smaller fragments + neutrons + energy. Used in nuclear reactors. FUSION: light nuclei (H-2, H-3) join to form heavier nucleus (He-4) + energy. Occurs in stars (including the sun). Fusion releases MORE energy per unit mass but is harder to achieve on Earth (requires extreme temperature and pressure)." },
  { id:"ph5_36", question:"The refractive index of glass is 1.5. What is the critical angle for total internal reflection at a glass-air boundary?", options:{A:"19.5°",B:"41.8°",C:"48.2°",D:"33.6°"}, answer:"B", explanation:"sin(c) = 1/n = 1/1.5 = 0.667. c = arcsin(0.667) = 41.8°. The critical angle is where the refracted ray travels at 90° (along the boundary). Above this angle, total internal reflection occurs. Used in optical fibres and diamond cut (high n = small critical angle = maximum internal reflection = maximum sparkle)." },
  { id:"ph5_37", question:"Which of the following best describes RESONANCE in a vibrating system?", options:{A:"A system vibrates at the same frequency as an applied external force, producing maximum amplitude",B:"Two waves cancel each other out by destructive interference",C:"A pendulum swings faster as it approaches the equilibrium position",D:"A stretched string vibrates at only one possible frequency"}, answer:"A", explanation:"RESONANCE: when the frequency of a periodic driving force matches the NATURAL FREQUENCY of the system, energy is transferred most efficiently and amplitude becomes maximum. Examples: Tacoma Bridge collapse, shattering a glass with sound, microwave oven heating water molecules. Resonance can be useful or destructive." },
  { id:"ph5_38", question:"A metal wire is stretched. Which property of the wire INCREASES?", options:{A:"Cross-sectional area",B:"Volume",C:"Electrical resistance",D:"Conductivity"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Stretching a wire: length L increases; cross-sectional area A decreases (volume is approximately constant). Resistance: R = ρL/A. Both an increase in L and a decrease in A cause R to increase. Conductivity (σ = 1/ρ) is a material property and does not change with stretching." },
  { id:"ph5_39", question:"What is the unit of electric field strength?", options:{A:"Tesla (T)",B:"Volt-metre (V·m)",C:"Newton per coulomb (N/C) or volt per metre (V/m)",D:"Ampere per metre (A/m)"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Electric field strength E = F/q (force per unit charge) → unit is N/C. Also, E = V/d (potential difference per unit distance) → unit is V/m. These are equivalent: N/C = V/m. Tesla is for magnetic field. Ampere/metre is for magnetic field intensity." },
  { id:"ph5_40", question:"Which of the following is an example of LONGITUDINAL wave motion?", options:{A:"Light waves",B:"Water waves",C:"Sound waves",D:"Electromagnetic waves"}, answer:"C", explanation:"LONGITUDINAL waves: particles vibrate PARALLEL to the direction of wave propagation (compressions and rarefactions). Sound is always longitudinal. TRANSVERSE waves: particles vibrate PERPENDICULAR to propagation. Light, radio waves, water waves (approximately), and all electromagnetic waves are transverse. Sound CANNOT travel in a vacuum; EM waves can." }
]; // end Physics[5]

DB["Mathematics"][5] = [
  { id:"ma5_01", question:"Convert 234₅ to base 10.", options:{A:"64",B:"69",C:"74",D:"59"}, answer:"B", explanation:"234₅ = 2×5² + 3×5¹ + 4×5⁰ = 2×25 + 3×5 + 4×1 = 50 + 15 + 4 = 69. Strategy: multiply each digit by the base raised to its positional power, then sum. Always start from the rightmost digit (position 0)." },
  { id:"ma5_02", question:"Convert 47₁₀ to base 5.", options:{A:"132₅",B:"142₅",C:"122₅",D:"152₅"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Divide repeatedly by 5 and record remainders: 47÷5 = 9 remainder 2; 9÷5 = 1 remainder 4; 1÷5 = 0 remainder 1. Read remainders upward: 142₅. Verify: 1×25 + 4×5 + 2×1 = 25+20+2 = 47. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_03", question:"Solve for x: 3x ≡ 2 (mod 5).", options:{A:"x = 1",B:"x = 2",C:"x = 3",D:"x = 4"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Test x = 1: 3×1=3 ≢ 2. x=2: 3×2=6≡1. x=3: 3×3=9≡4. x=4: 3×4=12=2×5+2 ≡ 2. ✓ So x = 4. Alternatively, find the modular inverse of 3 mod 5: since 3×2=6≡1, inverse of 3 is 2. Multiply both sides by 2: x ≡ 2×2 = 4 (mod 5)." },
  { id:"ma5_04", question:"Simplify: (3.2 × 10⁴) × (5 × 10⁻²).", options:{A:"1.6 × 10²",B:"1.6 × 10³",C:"1.6 × 10⁻²",D:"16 × 10²"}, answer:"B", explanation:"(3.2 × 5) × (10⁴ × 10⁻²) = 16 × 10² = 1.6 × 10³. When multiplying in standard form: multiply the decimal parts; add the powers of 10. Then adjust so the decimal part is between 1 and 10: 16 × 10² = 1.6 × 10³." },
  { id:"ma5_05", question:"Share ₦84,000 in the ratio 3:4:5 among three people. What is the LARGEST share?", options:{A:"₦21,000",B:"₦28,000",C:"₦35,000",D:"₦42,000"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Total parts = 3+4+5 = 12. One part = 84,000 ÷ 12 = 7,000. Largest share (5 parts) = 5 × 7,000 = ₦35,000. Shares: ₦21,000 : ₦28,000 : ₦35,000. Check: 21+28+35 = 84. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_06", question:"A price rises by 20% then falls by 20%. What is the net percentage change?", options:{A:"0% (no change)",B:"+4% increase",C:"−4% decrease",D:"+2% increase"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Start at 100. After 20% rise: 100 × 1.2 = 120. After 20% fall: 120 × 0.8 = 96. Net change = 96−100 = −4%. Key insight: successive percentage changes are NOT additive. The 20% fall applies to the HIGHER value, so the loss exceeds the gain." },
  { id:"ma5_07", question:"Solve |2x − 3| = 7.", options:{A:"x = 5 only",B:"x = −2 only",C:"x = 5 or x = −2",D:"x = 2 or x = −5"}, answer:"C", explanation:"|2x − 3| = 7 gives two equations: 2x − 3 = 7 → x = 5, or 2x − 3 = −7 → 2x = −4 → x = −2. Check: |2(5)−3| = |7| = 7 ✓; |2(−2)−3| = |−7| = 7 ✓. Always split absolute value equations into two cases." },
  { id:"ma5_08", question:"Simplify: 3/(x+1) + 2/(x−1).", options:{A:"5/(x²−1)",B:"(5x−1)/(x²−1)",C:"(5x+1)/(x²−1)",D:"5x/(x²−1)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Common denominator = (x+1)(x−1) = x²−1. Numerator: 3(x−1) + 2(x+1) = 3x−3+2x+2 = 5x−1. Result: (5x−1)/(x²−1). Verify at x=2: 3/3 + 2/1 = 1+2 = 3; (10−1)/(4−1) = 9/3 = 3. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_09", question:"The roots α and β of a quadratic satisfy α+β = 5 and αβ = 3. Find α² + β².", options:{A:"13",B:"16",C:"19",D:"22"}, answer:"C", explanation:"α² + β² = (α+β)² − 2αβ = (5)² − 2(3) = 25 − 6 = 19. This is Vieta's identity. Similarly: α³+β³ = (α+β)(α²−αβ+β²) = (α+β)[(α+β)²−3αβ]. These identities are frequently needed in JAMB algebra." },
  { id:"ma5_10", question:"Find the partial fractions of (3x+1)/[(x²+1)(x−1)].", options:{A:"(x+1)/(x²+1) + 1/(x−1)",B:"(−2x+1)/(x²+1) + 2/(x−1)",C:"2/(x²+1) + (x−1)/(x−1)",D:"(2x−1)/(x²+1) + 1/(x−1)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Write (3x+1)/[(x²+1)(x−1)] = (Ax+B)/(x²+1) + C/(x−1). Multiply through: 3x+1 = (Ax+B)(x−1) + C(x²+1). At x=1: 4 = C(2) → C=2. Expanding: 3x+1 = Ax²−Ax+Bx−B+2x²+2. Matching x²: A+2=0 → A=−2. Constant: −B+2=1 → B=1. Check x: −A+B = 2+1 = 3. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_11", question:"Find the sum of the first 20 even positive integers.", options:{A:"210",B:"380",C:"420",D:"440"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The first 20 even positive integers: 2, 4, 6, ..., 40. AP with a=2, d=2, n=20. S = n/2(2a+(n−1)d) = 10(4+38) = 10×42 = 420. Shortcut: sum of first n even integers = n(n+1) = 20×21 = 420. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_12", question:"A GP has first term 6 and common ratio 1/3. Find the sum to infinity.", options:{A:"7",B:"8",C:"9",D:"10"}, answer:"C", explanation:"S∞ = a/(1−r) = 6/(1−1/3) = 6/(2/3) = 6×(3/2) = 9. Condition for convergence: |r| < 1. Here r = 1/3, so convergence is guaranteed. The series: 6 + 2 + 2/3 + 2/9 + ... = 9." },
  { id:"ma5_13", question:"Three numbers in GP have sum 13 and product 27. Find the middle number.", options:{A:"1",B:"3",C:"9",D:"6"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Let the three numbers be a/r, a, ar (symmetrical GP form). Product = (a/r)(a)(ar) = a³ = 27 → a = 3. The middle term is a = 3. Verify sum: a(1/r + 1 + r) = 3(1/r+1+r) = 13 → 1/r+r = 10/3 → 3r²−10r+3=0 → (3r−1)(r−3)=0 → r=3 or 1/3. Numbers: 1, 3, 9. Sum = 13. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_14", question:"Evaluate Σr² for r = 1 to 10 using the formula Σr² = n(n+1)(2n+1)/6.", options:{A:"385",B:"275",C:"330",D:"420"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Σr² = 10(11)(21)/6 = 2310/6 = 385. The three standard summation formulae are: Σr = n(n+1)/2; Σr² = n(n+1)(2n+1)/6; Σr³ = [n(n+1)/2]². These must be memorised for JAMB Further Mathematics." },
  { id:"ma5_15", question:"Find the acute angle that the line y = √3·x + 1 makes with the positive x-axis.", options:{A:"30°",B:"45°",C:"60°",D:"90°"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Gradient m = √3. tan θ = m = √3. θ = arctan(√3) = 60°. Key angles: tan 30° = 1/√3; tan 45° = 1; tan 60° = √3. The angle of inclination is measured from the positive x-axis to the line anticlockwise. Since m = tan θ and m = √3, θ = 60°." },
  { id:"ma5_16", question:"Find the length of the tangent from the point (5, 4) to the circle x² + y² = 9.", options:{A:"√32",B:"4√2",C:"Both A and B (√32 = 4√2)",D:"√41"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Length of tangent = √(d² − r²) where d = distance from point to centre. Centre = (0,0), r = 3. d = √(25+16) = √41. Tangent length = √(41−9) = √32 = 4√2. Note: √32 = √(16×2) = 4√2, so A and C are both correct forms." },
  { id:"ma5_17", question:"Find the equation of the NORMAL to the curve y = x³ at the point (1, 1).", options:{A:"y = 3x − 2",B:"x + 3y = 4",C:"y = −3x + 4",D:"3x + y = 2"}, answer:"B", explanation:"dy/dx = 3x². At x=1: slope of tangent = 3. Slope of normal = −1/3 (negative reciprocal). Normal: y−1 = −1/3(x−1) → 3(y−1) = −(x−1) → 3y−3 = −x+1 → x+3y = 4. Verify: (1,1): 1+3 = 4. ✓" },
  { id:"ma5_18", question:"Differentiate y = e^(3x) + ln(2x).", options:{A:"3e^(3x) + 1/x",B:"3e^(3x) + 2/x",C:"e^(3x) + 1/x",D:"3e^(3x) + 2"}, answer:"A", explanation:"d/dx[e^(kx)] = ke^(kx) → d/dx[e^(3x)] = 3e^(3x). d/dx[ln(2x)] = 1/(2x) × 2 = 1/x (chain rule; or note ln(2x)=ln2+lnx so derivative = 1/x). Total: 3e^(3x) + 1/x." },
  { id:"ma5_19", question:"Differentiate y = x² sin x using the product rule.", options:{A:"x² cos x",B:"2x sin x",C:"2x sin x + x² cos x",D:"2x cos x + x² sin x"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Product rule: d/dx[uv] = u'v + uv'. Let u = x² (u' = 2x), v = sin x (v' = cos x). dy/dx = 2x·sin x + x²·cos x. This cannot be simplified further. The product rule is essential whenever two functions are multiplied." },
  { id:"ma5_20", question:"Evaluate ∫₀² e^(2x) dx.", options:{A:"½(e⁴ − 1)",B:"e⁴ − 1",C:"2(e⁴ − 1)",D:"½(e² − 1)"}, answer:"A", explanation:"∫e^(2x) dx = e^(2x)/2 + C. Evaluate: [e^(2x)/2]₀² = e^(4)/2 − e^(0)/2 = (e⁴−1)/2. Note: ∫e^(kx) dx = e^(kx)/k + C. At x=2: e^(4). At x=0: e^(0) = 1." },
  { id:"ma5_21", question:"Find ∫(2/x + 3x²) dx.", options:{A:"2ln|x| + x³ + C",B:"−2/x² + 6x + C",C:"2x + x³ + C",D:"ln|x²| + x³ + C"}, answer:"A", explanation:"∫2/x dx = 2ln|x|; ∫3x² dx = x³. Result: 2ln|x| + x³ + C. Note: ∫(1/x) dx = ln|x|, not x⁰/0. Also: 2ln|x| = ln|x²| (using log rules), so option D is equivalent to A. However, the standard form is 2ln|x| + x³ + C." },
  { id:"ma5_22", question:"Find the stationary points of y = x³ − 6x² + 9x + 1 and classify them.", options:{A:"Maximum at (3, 1) and minimum at (1, 5)",B:"Maximum at (1, 5) and minimum at (3, 1)",C:"Two minima at x = 1 and x = 3",D:"One stationary point at x = 2"}, answer:"B", explanation:"dy/dx = 3x²−12x+9 = 3(x−1)(x−3) = 0 → x=1 or x=3. d²y/dx² = 6x−12. At x=1: d²y = −6 < 0 → LOCAL MAXIMUM; y(1) = 1−6+9+1 = 5. At x=3: d²y = 6 > 0 → LOCAL MINIMUM; y(3) = 27−54+27+1 = 1. Maximum at (1,5), minimum at (3,1)." },
  { id:"ma5_23", question:"A square sheet of side 12 cm has squares of side x cut from each corner to form an open box. Find the value of x that maximises the volume.", options:{A:"x = 1 cm",B:"x = 2 cm",C:"x = 3 cm",D:"x = 4 cm"}, answer:"B", explanation:"V = x(12−2x)². dV/dx = (12−2x)² + x·2(12−2x)(−2) = (12−2x)[(12−2x) − 4x] = (12−2x)(12−6x) = 0. Solutions: x=6 (invalid, zero base) or x=2. V_max = 2(8)² = 128 cm³. Check d²V/dx² < 0 at x=2 to confirm maximum." },
  { id:"ma5_24", question:"Given cos θ = 4/5, find cos(θ/2) using the half-angle formula.", options:{A:"3/5",B:"3√10/10",C:"1/√5",D:"√(9/10)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Half-angle formula: cos(θ/2) = √[(1+cos θ)/2] = √[(1+4/5)/2] = √[(9/5)/2] = √[9/10] = 3/√10 = 3√10/10. Rationalise: 3/√10 × √10/√10 = 3√10/10. Options B and D are equivalent: √(9/10) = 3/√10 = 3√10/10." },
  { id:"ma5_25", question:"Solve 2sin θ − √3 = 0 for 0° ≤ θ ≤ 360°.", options:{A:"θ = 60° only",B:"θ = 60° and 300°",C:"θ = 60° and 120°",D:"θ = 30° and 150°"}, answer:"C", explanation:"2sin θ = √3 → sin θ = √3/2. Reference angle = 60°. sin is positive in Q1 and Q2. θ = 60° (Q1) and θ = 180°−60° = 120° (Q2). CAST diagram: sin positive in Q1 and Q2; cos positive in Q1 and Q4; tan positive in Q1 and Q3." },
  { id:"ma5_26", question:"Given tan θ = 3/4, find sec θ and cosec θ (assuming θ is acute).", options:{A:"sec θ = 5/4 and cosec θ = 5/3",B:"sec θ = 4/5 and cosec θ = 3/5",C:"sec θ = 5/3 and cosec θ = 5/4",D:"sec θ = 4/3 and cosec θ = 5/3"}, answer:"A", explanation:"tan θ = opp/adj = 3/4 → hyp = √(9+16) = 5. sin θ = 3/5, cos θ = 4/5. sec θ = 1/cos θ = 5/4. cosec θ = 1/sin θ = 5/3. The 3-4-5 right triangle is the standard JAMB Pythagorean triple." },
  { id:"ma5_27", question:"A cuboid has dimensions 3 cm × 4 cm × 5 cm. Find the angle between the longest space diagonal and the base.", options:{A:"30°",B:"36.9°",C:"45°",D:"53.1°"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Base diagonal = √(3²+4²) = √(9+16) = 5 cm. Space diagonal = √(5²+5²) = √50 = 5√2. Angle with base: tan α = height/base diagonal = 5/5 = 1 → α = 45°. The 3-4-5 base gives a diagonal of 5, which equals the height. So the angle is exactly 45°." },
  { id:"ma5_28", question:"In triangle ABC, a = 5, b = 7, c = 8. Using the cosine rule, find the angle C (opposite to side c = 8).", options:{A:"arccos(1/7) ≈ 81.8°",B:"arccos(−1/7) ≈ 98.2°",C:"arccos(1/5) ≈ 78.5°",D:"60°"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Cosine rule: cos C = (a²+b²−c²)/(2ab) = (25+49−64)/(2×5×7) = 10/70 = 1/7. C = arccos(1/7) ≈ 81.79°. Since cos C > 0, angle C is acute (less than 90°). The largest side (c=8) is opposite the largest angle." },
  { id:"ma5_29", question:"From a cumulative frequency table, the 25th value falls in the class 21−30 (class frequency 20, cumulative before = 15, lower boundary = 20.5). Find the median.", options:{A:"23.5",B:"25.0",C:"25.5",D:"26.5"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Median = L + [(n/2 − F)/f] × h. L = 20.5 (lower class boundary), n/2 = 25 (median position), F = 15 (cumulative frequency before this class), f = 20 (frequency of median class), h = 10 (class width). Median = 20.5 + [(25−15)/20] × 10 = 20.5 + 5 = 25.5." },
  { id:"ma5_30", question:"In a frequency distribution, the modal class is:", options:{A:"The class with the highest cumulative frequency",B:"The class with the highest frequency",C:"The middle class in the distribution",D:"The class containing the mean"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The MODAL CLASS is the class with the highest frequency (not cumulative frequency). The MODE is the midpoint of the modal class (in JAMB approximations) or can be estimated using the formula: Mode = L + [d₁/(d₁+d₂)] × h, where d₁ and d₂ are the differences in frequency from adjacent classes." },
  { id:"ma5_31", question:"A random variable X has the distribution: P(X=1)=0.2, P(X=2)=0.3, P(X=3)=0.3, P(X=4)=0.2. Find E(X).", options:{A:"2.0",B:"2.5",C:"3.0",D:"2.25"}, answer:"B", explanation:"E(X) = Σx·P(x) = 1(0.2)+2(0.3)+3(0.3)+4(0.2) = 0.2+0.6+0.9+0.8 = 2.5. Verify probabilities sum to 1: 0.2+0.3+0.3+0.2 = 1.0 ✓. E(X) is the mean of the probability distribution; it is the long-run average value." },
  { id:"ma5_32", question:"For two events A and B: P(A) = 0.5, P(B) = 0.4, P(A∩B) = 0.2. Find P(A∪B).", options:{A:"0.9",B:"0.7",C:"0.6",D:"1.1"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Addition rule: P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A∩B) = 0.5 + 0.4 − 0.2 = 0.7. The intersection is subtracted to avoid counting those outcomes twice. If A and B were mutually exclusive, P(A∩B) = 0 and P(A∪B) = P(A)+P(B) = 0.9." },
  { id:"ma5_33", question:"Solve the system: x+y+z=6, 2x−y+z=3, x+2y−z=4.", options:{A:"x=1, y=2, z=3",B:"x=2, y=2, z=2",C:"x=3, y=1, z=2",D:"x=1, y=3, z=2"}, answer:"B", explanation:"From (1) and (2): subtract: −x+2y = 3 − ... Add eq1 and eq3: 2x+3y = 10 (i). Subtract eq3 from eq1: −y+2z = 2 (ii). From eq1 and eq2: (1)−(2)/2... Systematic: eq1−eq2 gives −x+2y = 3 and x−y = −1; adding: y = 2. From eq1−eq3: −y+2z=2 → −2+2z=2 → z=2. From eq1: x+2+2=6 → x=2." },
  { id:"ma5_34", question:"A line has equation r = (1, 2, 3) + t(−1, 0, 2). At what value of t is the x-coordinate equal to −1?", options:{A:"t = 0",B:"t = 1",C:"t = 2",D:"t = −1"}, answer:"C", explanation:"x-component: x = 1 + t(−1) = 1−t. Set 1−t = −1 → t = 2. At t=2: position = (1−2, 2+0, 3+4) = (−1, 2, 7). Verify x = −1 ✓. Vector equations of lines: r = a + tb, where a is a position vector on the line and b is the direction vector." },
  { id:"ma5_35", question:"A solid hemisphere has radius 6 cm. Find the TOTAL surface area (curved + flat circular face).", options:{A:"72π cm²",B:"108π cm²",C:"144π cm²",D:"216π cm²"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Curved surface of hemisphere = 2πr² = 2π(36) = 72π. Flat circular base = πr² = π(36) = 36π. Total SA = 72π + 36π = 108π cm². Note: a full sphere has SA = 4πr². A hemisphere = half sphere + circular base = 2πr² + πr² = 3πr² = 3π(36) = 108π cm²." },
  { id:"ma5_36", question:"A cylinder of radius 4 cm and height 6 cm has a hemisphere of radius 4 cm placed on top. Find the TOTAL VOLUME.", options:{A:"96π cm³",B:"(288π + 128π/3) cm³",C:"416π/3 cm³",D:"Both B and C are equivalent"}, answer:"D", explanation:"V_cylinder = πr²h = π(16)(6) = 96π. V_hemisphere = (2/3)πr³ = (2/3)π(64) = 128π/3. Total = 96π + 128π/3 = 288π/3 + 128π/3 = 416π/3 cm³. Options B and C are algebraically equivalent. Always convert to a common denominator when adding terms with π." },
  { id:"ma5_37", question:"How many subsets does the set A = {p, q, r, s} have?", options:{A:"4",B:"8",C:"12",D:"16"}, answer:"D", explanation:"The number of subsets (power set size) of a set with n elements = 2ⁿ. Here n=4, so 2⁴ = 16 subsets. This includes the empty set {} and the set itself {p,q,r,s}. Number of PROPER subsets = 2ⁿ − 1 = 15 (excluding the set itself)." },
  { id:"ma5_38", question:"Apply De Morgan's law to simplify ¬(p ∧ q).", options:{A:"¬p ∧ ¬q",B:"¬p ∨ ¬q",C:"p ∨ q",D:"¬(p ∨ q)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"De Morgan's First Law: ¬(p ∧ q) ≡ ¬p ∨ ¬q. De Morgan's Second Law: ¬(p ∨ q) ≡ ¬p ∧ ¬q. Memory aid: break the bracket, change the connective (AND becomes OR, OR becomes AND), negate each. These laws are fundamental in logic and circuit design." },
  { id:"ma5_39", question:"Which of the following truth values is CORRECT for the biconditional p ↔ q?", options:{A:"True only when p is true and q is false",B:"True only when both p and q are true",C:"True when p and q have the SAME truth value",D:"Always false when p is false"}, answer:"C", explanation:"p ↔ q (if and only if): TRUE when both have the same truth value (TT or FF); FALSE when they differ (TF or FT). Truth table: T↔T=T; T↔F=F; F↔T=F; F↔F=T. This is the EQUIVALENCE connective. p↔q ≡ (p→q) ∧ (q→p)." },
  { id:"ma5_40", question:"y varies inversely as x². When x = 3, y = 8. Find y when x = 6.", options:{A:"4",B:"2",C:"1",D:"16"}, answer:"B", explanation:"y ∝ 1/x² → y = k/x². Find k: 8 = k/9 → k = 72. When x = 6: y = 72/36 = 2. Inverse variation: as x doubles (3→6), x² quadruples (9→36), so y decreases to ¼ of original: 8/4 = 2. ✓" }
]; // end Mathematics[5]